{"title_page": "Zygogynum oligostigma", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image =\n| image_caption =\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn |authors= Jaffr\u00e9, T. <i>et al.</i>|title= ''Zygogynum oligostigma'' |year= 1998|page= e.T37416A10052079 |accessdate= 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| genus = Zygogynum\n| species = oligostigma\n| authority = Vink\n}}\n\n'''''Zygogynum oligostigma''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Winteraceae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[New Caledonia]].  It is threatened by [[habitat loss]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3576407}}\n\n[[Category:Endemic flora of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Winteraceae]]\n[[Category:Endangered plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{magnoliid-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image =\n| image_caption =\n| status = EN\n| status_system = IUCN2.3\n| status_ref = <ref name=\"iucn\">{{cite iucn |authors= Jaffr\u00e9, T., ''et al.''|title= ''Zygogynum oligostigma'' |year= 1998|page= e.T37416A10052079 |accessdate= 20 April 2020}}</ref>\n| genus = Zygogynum\n| species = oligostigma\n| authority = Vink\n}}\n\n'''''Zygogynum oligostigma''''' is a species of [[plant]] in the family [[Winteraceae]]. It is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[New Caledonia]].  It is threatened by [[habitat loss]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3576407}}\n\n[[Category:Endemic flora of New Caledonia]]\n[[Category:Winteraceae]]\n[[Category:Endangered plants]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{magnoliid-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "tweak citation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zygogynum_oligostigma"}
{"title_page": "Rainwater harvesting", "text_new": "{{short description|Accumulation of rainwater for reuse}}\n[[File:03242012Taller sostenibilidad lore037.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Rainwater capture and storage system at the [[Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education, Mexico City]]]]\n'''Rainwater harvesting''' is a type of harvest in which the rain drops are collected and stored for the future use, rather than allowing them to run off. Rainwater can be collected from rivers or roofs and redirected to a deep pit (well, shaft, or borehole), [[Aquifer storage and recovery|aquifer]], a reservoir with percolation, or collected from dew or fog with nets or other tools. Its uses include water for gardens, [[livestock]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntotank.com/blog/rainwater-harvesting-for-livestock/|title=Rainwater Harvesting for Livestock|website=www.ntotank.com|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref> [[irrigation]], domestic use with proper treatment, indoor heating for houses, etc. The harvested water can also be used as [[drinking water]], longer-term storage, and for other purposes such as [[groundwater recharge]].\n\nRainwater harvesting is one of the simplest and oldest methods of [[Self-supply of water and sanitation|self-supply of water]] for households usually financed by the user.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rural-water-supply.net/en/self-supply |title=Rural Water Supply Network Self-supply site |last=Rural Water Supply Network |website=www.rural-water-supply.net/en/self-supply |access-date=2017-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== History of rain water harvesting  ==\nThe construction and use of [[cistern]]s to store rainwater can be traced back to the [[Neolithic Age]], when waterproof lime plaster cisterns were built in the floors of houses in village locations of the [[Levant]], a large area in Southwest Asia, south of the [[Taurus Mountains]], bound by the [[Mediterranean Sea]] in the west, the [[Arabian Desert]] in the south, and [[Mesopotamia]] in the east. By the late 40000 BC, cisterns were essential elements of emerging water management techniques used in [[dry-land farming]].<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Tanvir |first1=Sahu |last2=Antoniou |first2=George |last3=Angelakis |first3=Andreas |last-author-amp=yes |title=History of water cisterns: Legacies and lessons |journal=Water |date=2013 |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=1916\u20131940 |doi=10.3390/w5041916|url=https://repository.asu.edu/attachments/183018/content/History%20of%20water%20cisterns_2013.pdf }}</ref>\n\nMany ancient cisterns have been discovered in some parts of Jerusalem and the entire Land of Israel. At the site believed by some to be that of the biblical city of Ai (Khirbet et-Tell), a large cistern dating back to around 2500 BC was discovered that had a capacity of nearly {{Convert|1,700|m3|cuft|abbr=on}}. It was carved out of solid rock, lined with large stones, and sealed with clay to keep from leaking.<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\"/>\n\n[[File:Chidambaram Nataraja temple Shivaganga tank porch.jpg|thumb|Shivaganga Tank in Tamil Nadu]]\nThe Greek island of [[Crete]] is also known for its use of large cisterns for rainwater collection and storage during the [[Minoan civilization|Minoan]] period from 2,600 BC\u20131,100 BC. Four large cisterns have been discovered at [[Myrtos Pyrgos|Myrtos\u2013Pyrgos]], [[Archanes]], and Zakroeach. The cistern found at Myrtos-Pyrgos was found to have a capacity of more than {{Convert|80|m3|cuft|abbr=on}} and date back to 1700 BC.<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\"/>\n\nAround 300 BCE, farming communities in [[Balochistan]] (now located in Pakistan, Afghanistan, and Iran), and [[Kutch]], India, used rainwater harvesting for agriculture and many other uses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tn.gov.in/dtp/rainwater.htm |title=Rain water Harvesting |website= |publisher=[[Tamil Nadu State Government]], India |accessdate=23 January 2012}}</ref> Rainwater harvesting was done by [[Chola dynasty|Chola kings]] as well.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2010/07/17/stories/2010071754460800.htm |title=Believes in past, lives in future |date=17 July 2010 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |accessdate= |location=India}}</ref> Rainwater from the [[Brihadeeswarar temple]] (located in Balaganpathy Nagar, [[Thanjavur]], India) was collected in Shivaganga tank.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/08/04/stories/2003080402510500.htm |title=Rare Chola inscription found near Big Temple |date=24 August 2003 |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate= |location=India}}</ref> During the later Chola period, the V\u012br\u0101nam tank was built (1011 to 1037 CE) in the Cuddalore district of [[Tamil Nadu]] to store water for drinking and irrigation purposes. V\u012br\u0101nam is a 16-km-long tank with a storage capacity of {{Convert|1,465,000,000|cuft|m3|abbr=on}}.\n\nRainwater harvesting was also common in the [[Roman Empire]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kamash |first1=Zena |title=Archaeologies of Water in the Roman Near East |date=2010 |publisher=Gorgias Press}}</ref> While [[Roman aqueduct]]s are well-known, [[List of Roman cisterns|Roman cisterns]] were also commonly used and their construction expanded with the Empire.<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\"/> For example, in Pompeii, rooftop water storage was common before the construction of [[Aqua Augusta (Naples)|the aqueduct]] in the 1st century BC.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web |url=https://archserve.id.ucsb.edu/courses/arthistory/152k/water.html |title=Water Supply Systems: Cisterns, Reservoirs, Aqueducts {{!}} Roman Building Technology and Architecture, University of California Santa Barbara |website=ArchServe |access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> This history continued with the Byzantine Empire, for example the [[Basilica Cistern]] in Istanbul.\n\nThough little-known, for centuries the town of Venice depended on rainwater harvesting. The lagoon which surrounds Venice is brackish water, which is not suitable for drinking. The ancient inhabitants of Venice established a system of rainwater collection which was based on man-made insulated collection wells.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.venicebackstage.org/en/159/i-pozzi-veneziani|title=Venetian wells}}</ref> Water percolated down the specially designed stone flooring, and was filtered by a layer of sand, then collected at the bottom of the well. Later, as Venice acquired territories on the mainland, it started to import water by boat from local rivers, but the wells remained in use, and were especially important in time of war when access to the mainland water could be blocked by an enemy.\n\n-Tanvir\n\n=== Current uses ===\n==== Canada ====\n\n{{Main|Rainwater harvesting in Canada}}\n\nSeveral Canadians have started implementing rainwater harvesting systems for use in stormwater reduction, irrigation, laundry, and lavatory plumbing. Substantial reform to Canadian law since the mid-2000s has increased the use of this technology in agricultural, industrial, and residential use, but ambiguity remains amongst legislation in many provinces. Bylaws and local municipal codes often regulate rainwater harvesting.\n\n==== India ====\n* [[Tamil Nadu]] was the first state to make rainwater harvesting compulsory for every building to avoid [[Overdrafting|groundwater depletion]]. The scheme was launched in 2001 and has been implemented in all rural areas of Tamil Nadu. Posters all over Tamil Nadu including rural areas create awareness about harvesting rainwater. [http://www.tn.gov.in/dtp/rainwater.htm TN Govt site]. It gave excellent results within five years, and slowly every state took it as a role model. Since its implementation, [[Chennai]] had a 50% rise in water level in five years and the water quality significantly improved.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/tamil-nadu-praised-for-its-good-rainwater-harvesting-model/article2495647.ece |title=Tamil Nadu praised as role model for Rainwater Harvesting |journal=The Hindu |date=2011-09-29 |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n* [[Karnataka]]: In [[Bangalore]], adoption of rainwater harvesting is mandatory for every owner or the occupier of a building having the site area measuring {{Convert|60|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{Convert|40|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} and above and for newly constructed building measuring {{Convert|30|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{Convert|40|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} and above dimensions. In this regard, [[Bangalore Water Supply and Sewerage Board]] has initiated and constructed \u201cRain Water Harvesting Theme Park\u201d in the name of Sir [[M. Visvesvaraya]] in {{Convert|1.2|acre|m2|abbr=on}} of land situated at [[Jayanagar, Bangalore]]. In this park, 26 different type of rainwater harvesting models are demonstrated along with the water conservation tips. The auditorium on the first floor is set up with a \"green\" air conditioning system and will be used to arrange the meeting and showing of a video clip about the rainwater harvesting to students and general public.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bwssb.gov.in/bwssbuat/content/rain-water-harvesting-0 |title=Rain Water Harvesting BWSSB - Bangalore Water Supply and Sewerage Board |website=bwssb.gov.in}}</ref> An attempt has been made at the Department of Chemical Engineering, IISc, [[Bangalore]] to harvest rainwater using upper surface of a solar still, which was used for water distillation<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Anjaneyulu |first=L. |author2=Kumar, E. Arun |author3=Sankannavar, Ravi |author4=Rao, K. Kesava |last-author-amp=yes |date=13 June 2012 |title=Defluoridation of drinking water and rainwater harvesting using a solar still |journal=Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research |volume=51 |issue=23 |pages=8040\u20138048 |doi=10.1021/ie201692q}}</ref>\n* In [[Rajasthan]], rainwater harvesting has traditionally been practiced by the people of the [[Thar Desert]]. Many ancient water harvesting systems in Rajasthan have now been revived.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/Rural/Traditional1.htm#kund |title=Ancient water harvesting systems in Rajasthan |publisher=Rainwaterharvesting.org |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref> Water harvesting systems are widely used in other areas of Rajasthan, as well, for example the ''[[chauka]]'' system from the [[Jaipur district]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/rural/Improvised.htm |title=Chauka System |work=rainwaterharvesting.org: technology: rural: improvised |publisher=Centre for Science and Environment |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n* [[Maharashtra]]: At present, in [[Pune]], rainwater harvesting is compulsory for any new housing society to be registered.\n* In [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], rainwater harvesting is not mandatory. The Mumbai City council is planning to make rainwater harvesting mandatory for large societies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/bmc-to-make-rainwater-harvesting-mandatory-for-large-societies/17110192 |title=BMC to make rainwater harvesting mandatory for large societies|date=2016-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Israel ====\nThe Southwest Center for the Study of Hospital and Healthcare Systems in cooperation with Rotary International is sponsoring a rainwater harvesting model program across the country. The first rainwater catchment system was installed at an elementary school in Lod, Israel. The project is looking to expand to Haifa in its third phase. The Southwest Center has also partnered with the Water Resources Action Project of Washington, DC, which currently has rainwater harvesting projects in the West Bank. Rainwater harvesting systems are being installed in local schools for the purpose of educating schoolchildren about water conservation principles and bridging divides between people of different religious and ethnic backgrounds, all while addressing the [[water scarcity]] issue that the Middle East faces.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/rainwater-collection-system-saves-water-money-for-schools-1.8233 |title=Rainwater Collection System Saves Water, Money for Schools|newspaper=Haaretz|date=2009-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==== New Zealand ====\nAlthough New Zealand has plentiful rainfall in the West and South, for much of the country, rainwater harvesting is the normal practice for most rural housing and is encouraged by most councils.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gw.govt.nz/rainwater-tanks// |title=Rainwater tanks |date=28 April 2016 |publisher=Greater Wellington Regional Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414164122/http://www.gw.govt.nz/rainwater-tanks// |archivedate=14 April 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=21 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== Sri Lanka ====\nRainwater harvesting has been a popular method of obtaining water for agriculture and for drinking purposes in rural homes. The legislation to promote rainwater harvesting was enacted through the Urban Development Authority (Amendment) Act, No. 36 of 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lankarainwater.org/rwhsl/act_36_2007_e.pdf |title=Parliament Of The Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka}}</ref> Lanka rainwater harvesting forum<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lankarainwater.org/ |title=Lanka Rain Water Harvesting forum (LRWHF)}}</ref> is leading the Sri Lanka's initiative.\n\n==== South Africa ====\nThe South African Water Research Commission has supported research into rainwater harvesting. Reports on this research are available on their \"Knowledge Hub\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wrc.org.za/Pages/KH_DocumentsList.aspx?dt=1&su=8&ct=2&ms=4;7; |title=Rainwater harvesting |website=www.wrc.org.za |publisher=South African Water Research Commission |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> Studies in arid, semiarid, and humid regions have confirmed that techniques such as mulching, pitting, ridging, and modified run-on plots are effective for small-scale crop production.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://www.wrc.org.za/Knowledge%20Hub%20Documents/Research%20Reports/1465-1-11.pdf |title=Sustainable techniques and practices for water harvesting and conservation and their effective application in resource-poor agricultural production through participatory adaptive research : report to the Water Research Commission |vauthors=Everson C, Everson TM, Modi AT, Csiwila D, Fanadzo M, Naiken V, Auerbach RM, Moodley M, Mtshali SM, Dladla R |date=2011 |publisher=Water Research Commission |isbn=978-1-4312-0185-3 |location=Gezina [South Africa] |page=89 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> [[Hydraulic fracturing|hydrofracturing]] has regularly been used to improve the performance of water [[boreholes]]. From 1990 to 1992, 170 [[boreholes]] had been hydrofractured.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hydrofracture: State of the art in South Africa|journal=Hydrogeology Journal|volume=2|issue=2|pages=59\u201363|doi=10.1007/s100400050050|year=1994|last1=Less|first1=C.|last2=Andersen|first2=N. |last-author-amp=yes }}</ref>\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n{{Main|Rainwater harvesting in the United Kingdom}}\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], [[Rainwater tank|water butts]] are often found in domestic gardens and on [[Allotment (gardening)|allotments]] to collect rainwater, which is then used to water the garden. However, the British government's [[Code For Sustainable Homes]] encouraged fitting large underground tanks to newly built homes to collect rainwater for flushing toilets, watering, and washing. Ideal designs had the potential to reduce demand on mains water supply by half. The code was revoked in 2015.\n\n==== Other countries ====\n* In China, Argentina, and Brazil, [[wikiversity:Rainwater harvesting/Rooftop rainwater harvesting|rooftop rainwater harvesting]] is being done for livestock, water for small irrigation, and a way to replenish groundwater levels. [[Gansu]] province in China and semiarid [[Northeast Region, Brazil|northeast Brazil]] have the largest rooftop rainwater harvesting projects going on.\n* [[Thailand]] has the largest fraction of the population in the rural area relying on rainwater harvesting (currently around 40%).<ref name=\"JMP 2016\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wssinfo.org/fileadmin/user_upload/resources/Thailand.xls/ |title=Joint Monitoring Programme Thailand Data |last=JMP |date=2016 |website= |access-date=2017-03-13}}</ref> Rainwater harvesting was promoted heavily by the government in the 1980s. In the 1990s, after government funding for the collection tanks ran out, the private sector stepped in and provided several million tanks to private households, many of which continue to be used.<ref name=\"saladin20162\">{{Cite web |url=http://rural-water-supply.net/en/resources/details/759 |title=Rainwater Harvesting in Thailand - learning from the World Champions |last=Saladin |first=Matthias |date=2016 |website= |access-date=2017-03-13}}</ref> This is one of the largest examples of [[Self-supply of water and sanitation|self-supply of water]] worldwide.\n[[File:Rainwater harvesting tank (5981896147).jpg|thumb|Rainwater harvesting tank]]\n*In [[Bermuda]], the law requires all new construction to include rainwater harvesting adequate for the residents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-38222271 |title=Why houses in Bermuda have white stepped roofs |author=Harry Low |date=December 23, 2016 |work=BBC News |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Virgin Islands]] has a similar law.\n* In [[Senegal]] and [[Guinea-Bissau]], the houses of the [[Diola]]-people are frequently equipped with homebrew rainwater harvesters made from local, organic materials.\n* In the [[Irrawaddy Delta]] of [[Myanmar]], the groundwater is saline and communities rely on mud-lined rainwater ponds to meet their drinking water needs throughout the dry season. Some of these ponds are centuries old and are treated with great reverence and respect.\n* In the [[United States]], until 2009 in [[Colorado]], water rights laws almost completely restricted rainwater harvesting; a property owner who captured rainwater was deemed to be stealing it from those who have [[Prior appropriation water rights|rights to take water]] from the watershed. Now, residential well owners who meet certain criteria may obtain a permit to install a rooftop precipitation collection system (SB 09-080).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://water.state.co.us/DWRIPub/Documents/DWR_RainwaterFlyer.pdf |title=Rainwater Collection in Colorado |work=Colorado water law, notices. |publisher=Colorado Division of Water Resources |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref> Up to 10 large scale pilot studies may also be permitted (HB 09-1129).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cwcb.state.co.us/legal/documents/guidelines/finalrainwaterpilotcg.pdf |title=Criteria and Guidelines for the \"Rainwater Harvesting\" |date=January 28, 2010 |work=Pilot Project Program |publisher=Colorado Water Conservation Board (CWCB) |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref> The main factor in persuading the [[Colorado Legislature]] to change the law was a 2007 study that found that in an average year, 97% of the precipitation that fell in [[Douglas County, Colorado|Douglas County]], in the southern suburbs of [[Denver]], never reached a stream\u2014it was used by plants or evaporated on the ground. Rainwater catchment is mandatory for new dwellings in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]].<ref name=\"Johnson3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/29/us/29rain.html?em |title=It's Now Legal to Catch a Raindrop in Colorado |last=Johnson |first=Kirk |date=June 28, 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2009-06-30 |quote=Precipitation, every last drop or flake, was [[prior appropriation water rights|assigned ownership]] from the moment it fell in many Western states, making scofflaws of people who scooped rainfall from their own gutters. In some instances, the rights to that water were assigned a century or more ago.}}</ref> Texas offers a sales tax exemption on the purchase of rainwater harvesting equipment. Both Texas<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/tlodocs/82R/billtext/html/HB03391F.htm |title=82(R) H.B. No. 3391. Act relating to rainwater harvesting and other water conservation initiatives. \u2020 went into effect on September 1, 2011 |work=82nd Regular Session |publisher=Texas Legislature Online |accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref> and Ohio allow the practice even for potable purposes. Oklahoma passed the Water for 2060 Act in 2012, to promote pilot projects for rainwater and [[graywater]] use among other water-saving techniques.<ref name=\"NCSL3\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ncsl.org/issues-research/env-res/rainwater-harvesting.aspx |title=State Rainwater Harvesting Statutes, Programs and Legislation |work=NCSL |accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref>\n* In [[Beijing]], some housing societies are now adding rainwater in their main water sources after proper treatment.\n* In [[Ireland]], Professor Micheal Mcginley established a project to design a rainwater harvesting prototype in the biosystems design challenge module at [[University College Dublin]].\n\n\n== New approaches ==\n[[File:RainSaucer at Hogar Orphanage, Guatemala.JPG|thumb|Presentation of RainSaucer system to students at orphanage in Guatemala]]\nInstead of using the [[wikiversity:Rainwater harvesting/Rooftop rainwater harvesting|roof for catchment]], the RainSaucer, which looks like an upside-down umbrella, collects rain straight from the sky. This decreases the potential for contamination and makes RainSaucer a potential application for potable water in developing countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smartplanet.com/blog/design-architecture/harvesting-rainwater-for-more-than-greywater/485?tag=mantle_skin;content |title=Harvesting rainwater for more than greywater |work=SmartPlanet |accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Other applications of this free-standing rainwater collection approach are sustainable gardening and small-plot farming.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://localblu.com/2012/05/collect-up-to-10-gallons-of-water-per-inch-of-rain-with-rainsaucers-latest-standalone-rainwater-catchment/ |title=Collect up to 10 gallons of water per inch of rain with Rainsaucers' latest standalone rainwater catchment |last=Kumar |first=Ro |work=LocalBlu |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121217204145/http://localblu.com/2012/05/collect-up-to-10-gallons-of-water-per-inch-of-rain-with-rainsaucers-latest-standalone-rainwater-catchment/ |archivedate=17 December 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=11 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\nA Dutch invention called the [[Groasis Waterboxx]] is also useful for growing trees with harvested and stored dew and rainwater.\n\nTraditionally, stormwater management using [[detention basins]] served a single purpose. However, [[OptiRTC|optimized real-time control]] lets this infrastructure double as a source of rainwater harvesting without compromising the existing detention capacity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.high-profile.com/rainwater-harvesting-controls-in-cloud-by-steve-roy-marcus-quigley-and-chuck-raymond/ |title=Rainwater Harvesting - Controls in the Cloud |work=SmartPlanet |accessdate=11 January 2015|date=2013-10-03 }}</ref> This has been used in the [[EPA]] headquarters to evacuate stored water prior to storm events, thus reducing wet weather flow while ensuring water availability for later reuse. This has the benefit of increasing water quality released and decreasing the volume of water released during [[combined sewer overflow]] events.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/gallery/technology/2014/11/11/innovative-city-tech/8.html |title=The Tech Behind Smart Cities - Eliminating Water Pollution |last=O'Brien |first=Sara Ashley |work=CNN Money|accessdate=13 November 2014|date=2014-11-11 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.villanova.edu/content/dam/villanova/engineering/vcase/sym-presentations/3a3_Making%20Green_Andrea%20Braga.pdf |title=Making Green Work, and Work Harder |last=Braga |first=Andrea |publisher=Geosyntec |pages=5 |accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nGenerally, [[check dam]]s are constructed across the streams to enhance the percolation of surface water into the [[subsoil]] strata. The water percolation in the water-impounded area of the check dams can be enhanced artificially manyfold by loosening the subsoil strata and [[overburden]] using [[ANFO]] explosives as used in [[open cast mining]]. Thus, local [[aquifer]]s can be recharged quickly using the available surface water fully for use in the dry season.\n\n=== Nontraditional ===\nIn 1992, American artist [[Michael Jones McKean]] created an artwork in Omaha, Nebraska, at the [[Bemis Center for Contemporary Art]] that created a fully sustainable rainbow in the Omaha skyline. The project collected thousands of gallons of rainwater, storing the water in six daisy-chained 12,000 gallons tanks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.therainbow.org/overview/|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207115012/http://www.therainbow.org/overview/|archivedate=2013-12-07|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> The massive logistical undertaking, during its five-month span, was one of the largest urban rainwater harvesting sites in the American Midwest.\n\n=== Rainwater harvesting by freshwater-flooded forests ===\n[[File:Ratargul, Sylhet.jpg|thumb|[[Ratargul Swamp Forest|Ratagul Freshwater Flooded Forest]], [[Bangladesh]]]]\nRainwater harvesting is possible by growing [[Freshwater swamp forest|freshwater-flooded forests]] without losing the income from the used, submerged land.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/58789361/Rain-Water-Harvesting-by-Freshwater-Flooded-Forests |title=Rain Water Harvesting by Freshwater Flooded Forests}}</ref> The main purpose of the rainwater harvesting is to use the locally available rainwater to meet water requirements throughout the year without the need of huge capital expenditure. This would facilitate the availability of uncontaminated water for domestic, industrial, and irrigation needs.\n\n=== Rainwater harvesting by solar power panels ===\nGood quality water resource, closer to populated areas, is becoming scarce and costly for the consumers. In addition to solar and wind energy, rain water is major [[renewable resource]] of any land. Vast area is being covered by [[Photovoltaics|solar PV panels]] every year in all parts of the world. Solar panels can also be used for harvesting most of the rain water falling on them and drinking quality water, free from bacteria and suspended matter, can be generated by simple [[Water purification|filtration and disinfection]] processes as rain water is very low in [[salinity]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.windpowerengineering.com/environmental/wind-solar-powered-offgridbox-useful-hurricane-passes/ |title=Rain fed solar powered water purification systems. |accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2017/12/04/inverted-umbrella-brings-clean-water-clean-power-india/ |title=Inverted Umbrella Brings Clean Water & Clean Power To India |accessdate=5 December 2017|date=2017-12-04 }}</ref><ref name=inh>{{cite web |url=https://inhabitat.com/new-rooftop-solar-hydropanels-harvest-drinking-water-and-energy-at-the-same-time/  |title=New rooftop solar hydro panels harvest drinking water and energy at the same time |accessdate=2017-11-30}}</ref> Exploitation of rain water for value added products like bottled drinking water, makes solar PV power plants profitable even in high rainfall/ cloudy areas by the augmented income from value added drinking water generation.\nRecently cost effective Rain water collection in the already dug wells found to be highly effective in the bringing ground water level up in India.\n\n== Advantages ==\nRainwater harvesting provides the independent water supply during regional water restrictions, and in developed countries, is often used to supplement the main supply. It provides water when a drought occurs, can help mitigate flooding of low-lying areas, and reduces demand on wells which may enable groundwater levels to be sustained. It also helps in the availability of potable water, as rainwater is substantially free of salinity and other salts. Applications of rainwater harvesting in [[Integrated urban water management|urban water system]] provides a substantial benefit for both [[water supply]] and [[wastewater]] subsystems by reducing the need for [[clean water]] in water distribution systems, less generated [[stormwater]] in [[sewer system]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Behzadian |first=k |last2=Kapelan |first2=Z |date=2015 |title=Advantages of integrated and sustainability based assessment for metabolism based strategic planning of urban water systems |journal=Science of the Total Environment |volume=527-528 |pages=220\u2013231 |doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2015.04.097 |pmid= 25965035|hdl=10871/17351 |url=https://ore.exeter.ac.uk/repository/bitstream/10871/17351/1/Behzadian%20and%20Kapelan%202015b.pdf |bibcode=2015ScTEn.527..220B }}</ref> and a reduction in stormwater runoff polluting freshwater bodies.\n\nA large body of work has focused on the development of life cycle assessment and its costing methodologies to assess the level of environmental impacts and money that can be saved by implementing rainwater harvesting systems.<ref name=inh/>\n\n=== Independent water supply ===\nRainwater harvesting provides an independent water supply during water restrictions. In areas where clean water is costly, or difficult to come by, rainwater harvesting is a critical source of clean water. In developed countries, rainwater is often harvested to be used as a supplemental source of water rather than the main source, but the harvesting of rainwater can also decrease a household's water costs or overall usage levels. Rainwater is safe to drink if the consumers do additional treatments before drinking. Boiling water helps to kill germs. Adding another supplement to the system such as a first flush diverter is also a common procedure to avoid contaminants of the water. <ref> Centers of Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), 2013 Retrieved from https://www.cdc.gov/healthywater/drinking/private/rainwater-collection.html </ref>\n\n=== Supplemental in drought ===\nWhen drought occurs, rainwater harvested in past months can be used. If rain is scarce but also unpredictable, the use of a rainwater harvesting system can be critical to capturing the rain when it does fall. Many countries with arid environments, use rainwater harvesting as a cheap and reliable source of clean water. To enhance irrigation in arid environments, ridges of soil are constructed to trap and prevent rainwater from running down hills. Even in periods of low [[rainfall]], enough water is collected for crops to grow. Water can be collected from roofs and tanks can be constructed to hold large quantities of rainwater.\n\nIn addition, rainwater harvesting decreases the demand for water from wells, enabling groundwater levels to be further sustained rather than depleted.\n\n=== Life-cycle assessment ===\n[[Life-cycle assessment]] is a methodology used to evaluate the environmental impacts of a system from cradle-to-grave of its lifetime. Devkota et al,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Devkota |first1=J. |last2=Schlachter |first2=H. |last3=Anand |first3=C. |last4=Phillips |first4=R. |last5=Apul |first5=Defne |date=November 2013 |title=Development and application of EEAST: A lifecycle-based model for use of harvested rainwater and composting toilets in buildings |journal=Journal of Environmental Management |volume=130 |pages=397\u2013404 |doi=10.1016/j.jenvman.2013.09.015|pmid=24141064 }}</ref><ref name=\"Devkota 20152\">{{Cite journal |last1=Devkota |first1=Jay |last2=Schlachter |first2=Hannah |last3=Apul |first3=Defne |date=May 2015 |title=Life cycle based evaluation of harvested rainwater use in toilets and for irrigation |journal=Journal of Cleaner Production |volume=95 |pages=311\u2013321 |doi=10.1016/j.jclepro.2015.02.021}}</ref> developed such a methodology for rainwater harvesting, and found that the building design (e.g., dimensions) and function (e.g., educational, residential, etc.) play critical roles in the environmental performance of the system. The Economic and Environmental Analysis of Sanitations Technologies, [https://defneapul.wikispaces.com/Water+sustainability EEAST] model evaluates the greenhouse gas emissions and cost of such systems over the lifetime of a variety of building types.\n\nTo address the functional parameters of rainwater harvesting systems, a new metric was developed - the demand to supply ratio (D/S) - identifying the ideal building design (supply) and function (demand) in regard to the environmental performance of rainwater harvesting for toilet flushing. With the idea that supply of rainwater not only saves the potable water, but also saves the stormwater entering the combined sewer network (thereby requiring treatment), the savings in environmental emissions were higher if the buildings are connected to a combined sewer network compared to separate one.<ref name=\"Devkota 20152\"/>\n\n== System setup ==\n[[File:To Catch the Rain.pdf|thumb|''To Catch the Rain'', a 2017 book on rainwater harvesting]]\nRainwater harvesting systems can range in complexity, from systems that can be installed with minimal skills, to automated systems that require advanced setup and installation. The basic rainwater harvesting system is more of a plumbing job than a technical job, as all the outlets from the building's terrace are connected through a pipe to an underground tank that stores water.\n\nSystems are ideally sized to meet the water demand throughout the dry season, since it must be big enough to support daily water consumption. Specifically, the rainfall capturing area such as a building roof must be large enough to maintain adequate flow of water. The water storage tank size should be large enough to contain the captured water. \nFor low-tech systems, many low-tech methods are used to capture rainwater: rooftop systems, surface water capture and pumping the rainwater that has already soaked into the ground or captured in reservoirs and storing it in tanks (cisterns).\n\nBefore a rainwater harvesting system is built, use of digital tools is useful, for instance to detect if a region has a high rainwater harvesting potential or to estimate how much water is needed to fulfill a community's water needs. These tools can save time and money before a commitment to build a system is undertaken, in addition to making the project sustainable and long lasting.\n\n== Applications of rainwater harvesting ==\n=== Agriculture ===\n\nIn regards to [[Urban agriculture]] rainwater harvesting in urban areas reduces the impact of runoff and flooding. The combination of urban \u2018green\u2019 rooftops with rainwater catchments have been found to reduce building temperatures by more than 1.3 degrees Celsius.<ref name=\"Amos 174\u2013190\">{{Cite journal|last=Amos|first=Caleb Christian|last2=Rahman|first2=Ataur|last3=Karim|first3=Fazlul|last4=Gathenya|first4=John Mwangi|date=November 2018|title=A scoping review of roof harvested rainwater usage in urban agriculture: Australia and Kenya in focus|journal=Journal of Cleaner Production|volume=202|pages=174\u2013190|doi=10.1016/j.jclepro.2018.08.108|issn=0959-6526}}</ref> Rainwater harvesting in conjunction with urban agriculture would be a viable way to help meet the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals for cleaner and sustainable cities, health and wellbeing, and food and water security. The technology is available, however, needs to be remodeled in order to use water more efficiently, especially in an urban setting.\n\nKenya has already been successfully harvesting rainwater for toilets, laundry, and irrigation and areas in Australia use harvested rainwater for cooking and drinking.<ref name=\"Amos 174\u2013190\"/> Studies done by Stout et al researching the feasibility in India found RWH was most beneficial used for small scale irrigation, which provides income with the sales of produce,\u00a0and overflow used for groundwater recharge.<ref name=\"Amos 174\u2013190\"/>\n\nMissions to five Caribbean countries have shown that the capture and storage of rainwater runoff for later use is able to significantly reduce the risk of losing some or all of the year's harvest because of soil or water scarcity. In addition, the risks associated with flooding and soil erosion during high rainfall seasons would decrease. Small farmers, especially those farming on hillsides, could benefit the most from rainwater harvesting because they are able to capture runoff and decrease the effects of soil erosion.<ref name=\":83\">{{Cite journal |last=Fletcher-Paul |first=Dr. Lystra |date= |title=Feasibility Study of Rainwater Harvesting for Agriculture in the Caribbean Subregion |url=http://www.fao.org/3/a-bq747e.pdf |journal=FAO |volume= |pages= |via=}}</ref>\n\nMany countries, especially those with arid environments, use rainwater harvesting as a cheap and reliable source of clean water.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Rainwater Harvesting for Agriculture and Water Supply |last=Zhu |first=Qiang |publisher=Springer |year=2015 |isbn=978-981-287-964-6 |location=Beijing |pages=20 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> To enhance [[irrigation]] in arid environments, ridges of soil are constructed to trap and prevent rainwater from running down hills and slopes. Even in periods of low [[rainfall]], enough water is collected for crops to grow.<ref name=\":322\">{{Cite web |url=http://practicalaction.org/rainwater-harvesting-8 |title=Rainwater harvesting}}</ref> Water can be collected from roofs, dams and ponds can be constructed to hold large quantities of [[rain]]water so that even on days when little to no rainfall occurs, enough is available to irrigate crops.\n\n=== Domestic use ===\n* In China, Argentina, and Brazil, rooftop rainwater harvesting is used to provide drinking water, domestic water, water for livestock, water for small irrigation, and a way to replenish groundwater levels. [[Gansu]] province in China and semiarid [[Northeast Region, Brazil|northeast Brazil]] have the largest rooftop rainwater harvesting projects going on.\n* About 40% of Thailand's rural population utilizes rainwater harvesting.<ref name=\"JMP 2016\"/> Rainwater harvesting was promoted heavily by the government in the 1950s. In the 1990s, after government funding for the collection tanks ran out, the private sector stepped in and provided several million tanks to private households, many of which continue to be used today.<ref name=\"saladin20162\"/> This is one of the largest examples of [[Self-supply of water and sanitation|self-supply of water]] worldwide.\n* Rainwater harvesting is mandatory for new homes built in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=SANTA FE COUNTY Ordinance No. 2003-6: An Ordinance Amending Ordinance 1996-10, the Santa Fe County Land Development Code, Article III, Section 4.4.1 and Article III, Section 2.4.1 to require rainwater catchment systems for all commercial and residential development. |last= |first= |year=2003 |isbn= |location= |pages=}}</ref>\n* [[Texas]] offers a sales tax exemption for the purchase of rainwater harvesting equipment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/publications/shells/RainwaterHarvesting.pdf |title=Rainwater Harvesting |last=Texas Water Development Board |date=February 2018 |website=Water for Texas }}</ref>\n* Both Texas<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/tlodocs/82R/billtext/html/HB03391F.htm |title=82(R) H.B. No. 3391. Act relating to rainwater harvesting and other water conservation initiatives. \u2020 went into effect on September 1, 2011 |work=82nd Regular Session |publisher=Texas Legislature Online |accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref> and [[Ohio]] allow rainwater harvesting to be used even for potable purposes.\n* [[Oklahoma]] passed the Water for 2060 Act in 2012, to promote pilot projects for rainwater and [[graywater]] use among other water-saving techniques.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.owrb.ok.gov/2060/pdf/2014Waterfor2060factsheet.pdf |title=Water for 2060 Fact Sheet |last=Oklahoma Water Resources Board }}</ref>\n* In the [[United Kingdom]], [[Rainwater tank|water butts]] are often found in domestic gardens and on [[Allotment (gardening)|allotments]] to collect rainwater, which is then used to water the garden.\n\n=== Industry ===\nFrankfurt Airport has the biggest rainwater harvesting system in Germany. The system helps save approximately 1 million cubic meters of water per year. The cost of the system was 1.5 million dm (US$63,000) in 1993. This system collects water from roofs of the new terminal which has an area of 26,800 square metres. The water is collected in the basement of the airport in six tanks with a storage capacity of 100 cubic meters. The water is mainly used for toilet flushing, watering plants and cleaning the air conditioning system.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/international/germany.htm |title=The Rainwater Harvesting System at Mira Model School |website=www.rainwaterharvesting.org |access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref>\n\nRainwater harvesting was adopted at The Velodrome \u2013 The [[Olympic Park, London|London Olympic Park]] \u2013 in order to increase the sustainability of the facility. A 73% decrease in potable water demand by the park was estimated. Despite this, it was deemed that rainwater harvesting was a less efficient use of financial resources to increase sustainability than the park's blackwater recycling program.<ref name=\":93\">{{Cite web |url=http://learninglegacy.independent.gov.uk/documents/pdfs/sustainability/154-rainwater-harvesting-sust.pdf |title=Learning legacy: Lessons learned from the London 2012 Games construction project |date=2011 |website=Olympic Delivery Authority }}</ref>\n\n== Quality of water harvesting ==\nRainwater may need to be analyzed properly, and used in a way appropriate to its safety. In the [[Gansu]] province for example, [[solar water disinfection]] is used by boiling harvested rainwater in parabolic solar cookers before being used for drinking.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90781/6248934.html |last=Chen |first=Xuefei |title=Rainwater harvesting benefits farmers in Gansu |work=People's Daily Online |date=27 August 2007}}</ref> These so-called \"[[appropriate technology]]\" methods provide low-cost disinfection options for treatment of stored rainwater for drinking.\n\nWhile rainwater itself is a clean source of water, often better than groundwater or water from rivers or lakes,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hatch |first1=Jacob |title=The Many Benefits of Rainwater Harvesting |url=https://hydrationanywhere.com/the-many-benefits-of-rain-water-harvesting/ |website=Hydration Anywhere |publisher=Hydration Anywhere |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> the process of collection and storage often leaves the water polluted and non-potable. Rainwater harvested from roofs can contain human, animal and bird [[feces]], [[moss]]es and [[lichen]]s, windblown dust, particulates from urban pollution, pesticides, and inorganic [[ion]]s from the sea ([[Calcium|Ca]], [[Magnesium|Mg]], [[Sodium|Na]], [[Potassium|K]], [[Chlorine|Cl]], [[sulfate|SO<sub>4</sub>]]), and dissolved gases ([[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]], [[nitrogen oxide|NO<sub>x</sub>]], [[sulfur oxide|SO<sub>x</sub>]]). High levels of pesticide have been found in rainwater in Europe with the highest concentrations occurring in the first rain immediately after a dry spell;<ref>{{Cite magazine |last1=Pearce |first1=Fred |last2=Mackenzie |first2=Debora |date=3 April 1999 |title=It's raining pesticides |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg16221803-100-its-raining-pesticides/ |magazine=New Scientist |issue=2180 |access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref> the concentration of these and other contaminants are reduced significantly by diverting the [[First flush|initial flow]] of run-off water to waste. Improved water quality can also be obtained by using a floating draw-off mechanism (rather than from the base of the tank) and by using a series of tanks, withdraw from the last in series. Prefiltration is a common practice used in the industry to keep the system healthy and ensure that the water entering the tank is free of large sediments.\n\nA very interesting concept of rain water harvesting and cleaning it with solar energy for rural household drinking purposes has been developed by [[Nimbkar Agricultural Research Institute]]. <ref>[https://www.currentscience.ac.in/Volumes/118/06/0872.pdf Low cost drinking water technology \u2013 rainwater harvesting with solar purification. Current Science, Vol. 118, No.6, 25 March 2020]</ref>\n\nConceptually, a water supply system should match the quality of water with the end use. However, in most of the developed world, high-quality potable water is used for all end uses. This approach wastes money and energy and imposes unnecessary impacts to the environment. Supplying rainwater that has gone through preliminary filtration measures for nonpotable water uses, such as toilet flushing, irrigation and laundry, may be a significant part of a sustainable water management strategy.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ecology}}\n* {{annotated link|Air well (condenser)}}\n* {{annotated link|Atmospheric water generator}} \n* {{annotated link|Deepwater rice}}\n* {{annotated link|Detention basin}} \n* {{annotated link|Peak water}} \n* {{annotated link|Retention basin}}\n* {{annotated link|Water conservation}}\n* [https://www.schoolproject.in/working-model-of-rainwater-harvesting-for-school-project/ DIY Rainwater Harvesting Project for students]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no | n=no | q=no | s=no |v=no}}\n{{Wikiversity}}\n\n[[Category:Rainwater harvesting|*]]\n[[Category:Water supply]]\n[[Category:Water conservation]]\n[[Category:Irrigation]]\n[[Category:Appropriate technology]]\n[[Category:Hydrology and urban planning]]\n[[Category:DIY culture]]\n[[Category:Aquifers]]\n[[Category:Sustainable gardening]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Accumulation of rainwater for reuse}}\n[[File:03242012Taller sostenibilidad lore037.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Rainwater capture and storage system at the [[Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education, Mexico City]]]]\n'''Rainwater harvesting''' is a type of harvest in which the rain drops are collected and stored for the future use, rather than allowing them to run off. Rainwater can be collected from rivers or roofs and redirected to a deep pit (well, shaft, or borehole), [[Aquifer storage and recovery|aquifer]], a reservoir with percolation, or collected from dew or fog with nets or other tools. Its uses include water for gardens, [[livestock]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntotank.com/blog/rainwater-harvesting-for-livestock/|title=Rainwater Harvesting for Livestock|website=www.ntotank.com|access-date=2018-11-21}}</ref> [[irrigation]], domestic use with proper treatment, indoor heating for houses, etc. The harvested water can also be used as [[drinking water]], longer-term storage, and for other purposes such as [[groundwater recharge]].\n\nRainwater harvesting is one of the simplest and oldest methods of [[Self-supply of water and sanitation|self-supply of water]] for households usually financed by the user.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rural-water-supply.net/en/self-supply |title=Rural Water Supply Network Self-supply site |last=Rural Water Supply Network |website=www.rural-water-supply.net/en/self-supply |access-date=2017-03-19}}</ref>\n\n== History of rain water harvesting ==\nThe construction and use of [[cistern]]s to store rainwater can be traced back to the [[Neolithic Age]], when waterproof lime plaster cisterns were built in the floors of houses in village locations of the [[Levant]], a large area in Southwest Asia, south of the [[Taurus Mountains]], bound by the [[Mediterranean Sea]] in the west, the [[Arabian Desert]] in the south, and [[Mesopotamia]] in the east. By the late 40000 BC, cisterns were essential elements of emerging water management techniques used in [[dry-land farming]].<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\">{{cite journal |last1=Mays |first1=Larry |last2=Antoniou |first2=George |last3=Angelakis |first3=Andreas |last-author-amp=yes |title=History of water cisterns: Legacies and lessons |journal=Water |date=2013 |volume=5 |issue=4 |pages=1916\u20131940 |doi=10.3390/w5041916|url=https://repository.asu.edu/attachments/183018/content/History%20of%20water%20cisterns_2013.pdf }}</ref>\n\nMany ancient cisterns have been discovered in some parts of Jerusalem and the entire Land of Israel. At the site believed by some to be that of the biblical city of Ai (Khirbet et-Tell), a large cistern dating back to around 2500 BC was discovered that had a capacity of nearly {{Convert|1,700|m3|cuft|abbr=on}}. It was carved out of solid rock, lined with large stones, and sealed with clay to keep from leaking.<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\"/>\n\n[[File:Chidambaram Nataraja temple Shivaganga tank porch.jpg|thumb|Shivaganga Tank in Tamil Nadu]]\nThe Greek island of [[Crete]] is also known for its use of large cisterns for rainwater collection and storage during the [[Minoan civilization|Minoan]] period from 2,600 BC\u20131,100 BC. Four large cisterns have been discovered at [[Myrtos Pyrgos|Myrtos\u2013Pyrgos]], [[Archanes]], and Zakroeach. The cistern found at Myrtos-Pyrgos was found to have a capacity of more than {{Convert|80|m3|cuft|abbr=on}} and date back to 1700 BC.<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\"/>\n\nAround 300 BCE, farming communities in [[Balochistan]] (now located in Pakistan, Afghanistan, and Iran), and [[Kutch]], India, used rainwater harvesting for agriculture and many other uses.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.tn.gov.in/dtp/rainwater.htm |title=Rain water Harvesting |website= |publisher=[[Tamil Nadu State Government]], India |accessdate=23 January 2012}}</ref> Rainwater harvesting was done by [[Chola dynasty|Chola kings]] as well.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/mp/2010/07/17/stories/2010071754460800.htm |title=Believes in past, lives in future |date=17 July 2010 |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |accessdate= |location=India}}</ref> Rainwater from the [[Brihadeeswarar temple]] (located in Balaganpathy Nagar, [[Thanjavur]], India) was collected in Shivaganga tank.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.hindu.com/2003/08/04/stories/2003080402510500.htm |title=Rare Chola inscription found near Big Temple |date=24 August 2003 |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate= |location=India}}</ref> During the later Chola period, the V\u012br\u0101nam tank was built (1011 to 1037 CE) in the Cuddalore district of [[Tamil Nadu]] to store water for drinking and irrigation purposes. V\u012br\u0101nam is a 16-km-long tank with a storage capacity of {{Convert|1,465,000,000|cuft|m3|abbr=on}}.\n\nRainwater harvesting was also common in the [[Roman Empire]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Kamash |first1=Zena |title=Archaeologies of Water in the Roman Near East |date=2010 |publisher=Gorgias Press}}</ref> While [[Roman aqueduct]]s are well-known, [[List of Roman cisterns|Roman cisterns]] were also commonly used and their construction expanded with the Empire.<ref name=\"Mays et al. 2013\"/> For example, in Pompeii, rooftop water storage was common before the construction of [[Aqua Augusta (Naples)|the aqueduct]] in the 1st century BC.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web |url=https://archserve.id.ucsb.edu/courses/arthistory/152k/water.html |title=Water Supply Systems: Cisterns, Reservoirs, Aqueducts {{!}} Roman Building Technology and Architecture, University of California Santa Barbara |website=ArchServe |access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> This history continued with the Byzantine Empire, for example the [[Basilica Cistern]] in Istanbul.\n\nThough little-known, for centuries the town of Venice depended on rainwater harvesting. The lagoon which surrounds Venice is brackish water, which is not suitable for drinking. The ancient inhabitants of Venice established a system of rainwater collection which was based on man-made insulated collection wells.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.venicebackstage.org/en/159/i-pozzi-veneziani|title=Venetian wells}}</ref> Water percolated down the specially designed stone flooring, and was filtered by a layer of sand, then collected at the bottom of the well. Later, as Venice acquired territories on the mainland, it started to import water by boat from local rivers, but the wells remained in use, and were especially important in time of war when access to the mainland water could be blocked by an enemy.\n\n=== Current uses ===\n==== Canada ====\n\n{{Main|Rainwater harvesting in Canada}}\n\nSeveral Canadians have started implementing rainwater harvesting systems for use in stormwater reduction, irrigation, laundry, and lavatory plumbing. Substantial reform to Canadian law since the mid-2000s has increased the use of this technology in agricultural, industrial, and residential use, but ambiguity remains amongst legislation in many provinces. Bylaws and local municipal codes often regulate rainwater harvesting.\n\n==== India ====\n* [[Tamil Nadu]] was the first state to make rainwater harvesting compulsory for every building to avoid [[Overdrafting|groundwater depletion]]. The scheme was launched in 2001 and has been implemented in all rural areas of Tamil Nadu. Posters all over Tamil Nadu including rural areas create awareness about harvesting rainwater. [http://www.tn.gov.in/dtp/rainwater.htm TN Govt site]. It gave excellent results within five years, and slowly every state took it as a role model. Since its implementation, [[Chennai]] had a 50% rise in water level in five years and the water quality significantly improved.<ref>{{Cite newspaper |url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/tamil-nadu-praised-for-its-good-rainwater-harvesting-model/article2495647.ece |title=Tamil Nadu praised as role model for Rainwater Harvesting |journal=The Hindu |date=2011-09-29 |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref>\n* [[Karnataka]]: In [[Bangalore]], adoption of rainwater harvesting is mandatory for every owner or the occupier of a building having the site area measuring {{Convert|60|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{Convert|40|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} and above and for newly constructed building measuring {{Convert|30|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{Convert|40|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} and above dimensions. In this regard, [[Bangalore Water Supply and Sewerage Board]] has initiated and constructed \u201cRain Water Harvesting Theme Park\u201d in the name of Sir [[M. Visvesvaraya]] in {{Convert|1.2|acre|m2|abbr=on}} of land situated at [[Jayanagar, Bangalore]]. In this park, 26 different type of rainwater harvesting models are demonstrated along with the water conservation tips. The auditorium on the first floor is set up with a \"green\" air conditioning system and will be used to arrange the meeting and showing of a video clip about the rainwater harvesting to students and general public.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bwssb.gov.in/bwssbuat/content/rain-water-harvesting-0 |title=Rain Water Harvesting BWSSB - Bangalore Water Supply and Sewerage Board |website=bwssb.gov.in}}</ref> An attempt has been made at the Department of Chemical Engineering, IISc, [[Bangalore]] to harvest rainwater using upper surface of a solar still, which was used for water distillation<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Anjaneyulu |first=L. |author2=Kumar, E. Arun |author3=Sankannavar, Ravi |author4=Rao, K. Kesava |last-author-amp=yes |date=13 June 2012 |title=Defluoridation of drinking water and rainwater harvesting using a solar still |journal=Industrial & Engineering Chemistry Research |volume=51 |issue=23 |pages=8040\u20138048 |doi=10.1021/ie201692q}}</ref>\n* In [[Rajasthan]], rainwater harvesting has traditionally been practiced by the people of the [[Thar Desert]]. Many ancient water harvesting systems in Rajasthan have now been revived.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/Rural/Traditional1.htm#kund |title=Ancient water harvesting systems in Rajasthan |publisher=Rainwaterharvesting.org |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref> Water harvesting systems are widely used in other areas of Rajasthan, as well, for example the ''[[chauka]]'' system from the [[Jaipur district]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/rural/Improvised.htm |title=Chauka System |work=rainwaterharvesting.org: technology: rural: improvised |publisher=Centre for Science and Environment |accessdate=2013-10-23}}</ref>\n* [[Maharashtra]]: At present, in [[Pune]], rainwater harvesting is compulsory for any new housing society to be registered.\n* In [[Mumbai]], [[Maharashtra]], rainwater harvesting is not mandatory. The Mumbai City council is planning to make rainwater harvesting mandatory for large societies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/bmc-to-make-rainwater-harvesting-mandatory-for-large-societies/17110192 |title=BMC to make rainwater harvesting mandatory for large societies|date=2016-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==== Israel ====\nThe Southwest Center for the Study of Hospital and Healthcare Systems in cooperation with Rotary International is sponsoring a rainwater harvesting model program across the country. The first rainwater catchment system was installed at an elementary school in Lod, Israel. The project is looking to expand to Haifa in its third phase. The Southwest Center has also partnered with the Water Resources Action Project of Washington, DC, which currently has rainwater harvesting projects in the West Bank. Rainwater harvesting systems are being installed in local schools for the purpose of educating schoolchildren about water conservation principles and bridging divides between people of different religious and ethnic backgrounds, all while addressing the [[water scarcity]] issue that the Middle East faces.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.haaretz.com/rainwater-collection-system-saves-water-money-for-schools-1.8233 |title=Rainwater Collection System Saves Water, Money for Schools|newspaper=Haaretz|date=2009-09-09}}</ref>\n\n==== New Zealand ====\nAlthough New Zealand has plentiful rainfall in the West and South, for much of the country, rainwater harvesting is the normal practice for most rural housing and is encouraged by most councils.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.gw.govt.nz/rainwater-tanks// |title=Rainwater tanks |date=28 April 2016 |publisher=Greater Wellington Regional Council |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160414164122/http://www.gw.govt.nz/rainwater-tanks// |archivedate=14 April 2016 |url-status=dead |access-date=21 March 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==== Sri Lanka ====\nRainwater harvesting has been a popular method of obtaining water for agriculture and for drinking purposes in rural homes. The legislation to promote rainwater harvesting was enacted through the Urban Development Authority (Amendment) Act, No. 36 of 2007.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lankarainwater.org/rwhsl/act_36_2007_e.pdf |title=Parliament Of The Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka}}</ref> Lanka rainwater harvesting forum<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.lankarainwater.org/ |title=Lanka Rain Water Harvesting forum (LRWHF)}}</ref> is leading the Sri Lanka's initiative.\n\n==== South Africa ====\nThe South African Water Research Commission has supported research into rainwater harvesting. Reports on this research are available on their \"Knowledge Hub\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.wrc.org.za/Pages/KH_DocumentsList.aspx?dt=1&su=8&ct=2&ms=4;7; |title=Rainwater harvesting |website=www.wrc.org.za |publisher=South African Water Research Commission |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> Studies in arid, semiarid, and humid regions have confirmed that techniques such as mulching, pitting, ridging, and modified run-on plots are effective for small-scale crop production.<ref>{{Cite book |url=http://www.wrc.org.za/Knowledge%20Hub%20Documents/Research%20Reports/1465-1-11.pdf |title=Sustainable techniques and practices for water harvesting and conservation and their effective application in resource-poor agricultural production through participatory adaptive research : report to the Water Research Commission |vauthors=Everson C, Everson TM, Modi AT, Csiwila D, Fanadzo M, Naiken V, Auerbach RM, Moodley M, Mtshali SM, Dladla R |date=2011 |publisher=Water Research Commission |isbn=978-1-4312-0185-3 |location=Gezina [South Africa] |page=89 |accessdate=27 August 2014}}</ref> [[Hydraulic fracturing|hydrofracturing]] has regularly been used to improve the performance of water [[boreholes]]. From 1990 to 1992, 170 [[boreholes]] had been hydrofractured.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Hydrofracture: State of the art in South Africa|journal=Hydrogeology Journal|volume=2|issue=2|pages=59\u201363|doi=10.1007/s100400050050|year=1994|last1=Less|first1=C.|last2=Andersen|first2=N. |last-author-amp=yes }}</ref>\n\n==== United Kingdom ====\n{{Main|Rainwater harvesting in the United Kingdom}}\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], [[Rainwater tank|water butts]] are often found in domestic gardens and on [[Allotment (gardening)|allotments]] to collect rainwater, which is then used to water the garden. However, the British government's [[Code For Sustainable Homes]] encouraged fitting large underground tanks to newly built homes to collect rainwater for flushing toilets, watering, and washing. Ideal designs had the potential to reduce demand on mains water supply by half. The code was revoked in 2015.\n\n==== Other countries ====\n* In China, Argentina, and Brazil, [[wikiversity:Rainwater harvesting/Rooftop rainwater harvesting|rooftop rainwater harvesting]] is being done for livestock, water for small irrigation, and a way to replenish groundwater levels. [[Gansu]] province in China and semiarid [[Northeast Region, Brazil|northeast Brazil]] have the largest rooftop rainwater harvesting projects going on.\n* [[Thailand]] has the largest fraction of the population in the rural area relying on rainwater harvesting (currently around 40%).<ref name=\"JMP 2016\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.wssinfo.org/fileadmin/user_upload/resources/Thailand.xls/ |title=Joint Monitoring Programme Thailand Data |last=JMP |date=2016 |website= |access-date=2017-03-13}}</ref> Rainwater harvesting was promoted heavily by the government in the 1980s. In the 1990s, after government funding for the collection tanks ran out, the private sector stepped in and provided several million tanks to private households, many of which continue to be used.<ref name=\"saladin20162\">{{Cite web |url=http://rural-water-supply.net/en/resources/details/759 |title=Rainwater Harvesting in Thailand - learning from the World Champions |last=Saladin |first=Matthias |date=2016 |website= |access-date=2017-03-13}}</ref> This is one of the largest examples of [[Self-supply of water and sanitation|self-supply of water]] worldwide.\n[[File:Rainwater harvesting tank (5981896147).jpg|thumb|Rainwater harvesting tank]]\n*In [[Bermuda]], the law requires all new construction to include rainwater harvesting adequate for the residents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-38222271 |title=Why houses in Bermuda have white stepped roofs |author=Harry Low |date=December 23, 2016 |work=BBC News |accessdate=2016-12-23}}</ref>\n* The [[U.S. Virgin Islands]] has a similar law.\n* In [[Senegal]] and [[Guinea-Bissau]], the houses of the [[Diola]]-people are frequently equipped with homebrew rainwater harvesters made from local, organic materials.\n* In the [[Irrawaddy Delta]] of [[Myanmar]], the groundwater is saline and communities rely on mud-lined rainwater ponds to meet their drinking water needs throughout the dry season. Some of these ponds are centuries old and are treated with great reverence and respect.\n* In the [[United States]], until 2009 in [[Colorado]], water rights laws almost completely restricted rainwater harvesting; a property owner who captured rainwater was deemed to be stealing it from those who have [[Prior appropriation water rights|rights to take water]] from the watershed. Now, residential well owners who meet certain criteria may obtain a permit to install a rooftop precipitation collection system (SB 09-080).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://water.state.co.us/DWRIPub/Documents/DWR_RainwaterFlyer.pdf |title=Rainwater Collection in Colorado |work=Colorado water law, notices. |publisher=Colorado Division of Water Resources |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref> Up to 10 large scale pilot studies may also be permitted (HB 09-1129).<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cwcb.state.co.us/legal/documents/guidelines/finalrainwaterpilotcg.pdf |title=Criteria and Guidelines for the \"Rainwater Harvesting\" |date=January 28, 2010 |work=Pilot Project Program |publisher=Colorado Water Conservation Board (CWCB) |accessdate=2012-03-24}}</ref> The main factor in persuading the [[Colorado Legislature]] to change the law was a 2007 study that found that in an average year, 97% of the precipitation that fell in [[Douglas County, Colorado|Douglas County]], in the southern suburbs of [[Denver]], never reached a stream\u2014it was used by plants or evaporated on the ground. Rainwater catchment is mandatory for new dwellings in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]].<ref name=\"Johnson3\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/29/us/29rain.html?em |title=It's Now Legal to Catch a Raindrop in Colorado |last=Johnson |first=Kirk |date=June 28, 2009 |work=[[The New York Times]] |accessdate=2009-06-30 |quote=Precipitation, every last drop or flake, was [[prior appropriation water rights|assigned ownership]] from the moment it fell in many Western states, making scofflaws of people who scooped rainfall from their own gutters. In some instances, the rights to that water were assigned a century or more ago.}}</ref> Texas offers a sales tax exemption on the purchase of rainwater harvesting equipment. Both Texas<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/tlodocs/82R/billtext/html/HB03391F.htm |title=82(R) H.B. No. 3391. Act relating to rainwater harvesting and other water conservation initiatives. \u2020 went into effect on September 1, 2011 |work=82nd Regular Session |publisher=Texas Legislature Online |accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref> and Ohio allow the practice even for potable purposes. Oklahoma passed the Water for 2060 Act in 2012, to promote pilot projects for rainwater and [[graywater]] use among other water-saving techniques.<ref name=\"NCSL3\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ncsl.org/issues-research/env-res/rainwater-harvesting.aspx |title=State Rainwater Harvesting Statutes, Programs and Legislation |work=NCSL |accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref>\n* In [[Beijing]], some housing societies are now adding rainwater in their main water sources after proper treatment.\n* In [[Ireland]], Professor Micheal Mcginley established a project to design a rainwater harvesting prototype in the biosystems design challenge module at [[University College Dublin]].\n\n== New approaches ==\n[[File:RainSaucer at Hogar Orphanage, Guatemala.JPG|thumb|Presentation of RainSaucer system to students at orphanage in Guatemala]]\nInstead of using the [[wikiversity:Rainwater harvesting/Rooftop rainwater harvesting|roof for catchment]], the RainSaucer, which looks like an upside-down umbrella, collects rain straight from the sky. This decreases the potential for contamination and makes RainSaucer a potential application for potable water in developing countries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smartplanet.com/blog/design-architecture/harvesting-rainwater-for-more-than-greywater/485?tag=mantle_skin;content |title=Harvesting rainwater for more than greywater |work=SmartPlanet |accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref> Other applications of this free-standing rainwater collection approach are sustainable gardening and small-plot farming.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://localblu.com/2012/05/collect-up-to-10-gallons-of-water-per-inch-of-rain-with-rainsaucers-latest-standalone-rainwater-catchment/ |title=Collect up to 10 gallons of water per inch of rain with Rainsaucers' latest standalone rainwater catchment |last=Kumar |first=Ro |work=LocalBlu |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121217204145/http://localblu.com/2012/05/collect-up-to-10-gallons-of-water-per-inch-of-rain-with-rainsaucers-latest-standalone-rainwater-catchment/ |archivedate=17 December 2012 |url-status=dead |accessdate=11 February 2013 }}</ref>\n\nA Dutch invention called the [[Groasis Waterboxx]] is also useful for growing trees with harvested and stored dew and rainwater.\n\nTraditionally, stormwater management using [[detention basins]] served a single purpose. However, [[OptiRTC|optimized real-time control]] lets this infrastructure double as a source of rainwater harvesting without compromising the existing detention capacity.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.high-profile.com/rainwater-harvesting-controls-in-cloud-by-steve-roy-marcus-quigley-and-chuck-raymond/ |title=Rainwater Harvesting - Controls in the Cloud |work=SmartPlanet |accessdate=11 January 2015|date=2013-10-03 }}</ref> This has been used in the [[EPA]] headquarters to evacuate stored water prior to storm events, thus reducing wet weather flow while ensuring water availability for later reuse. This has the benefit of increasing water quality released and decreasing the volume of water released during [[combined sewer overflow]] events.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/gallery/technology/2014/11/11/innovative-city-tech/8.html |title=The Tech Behind Smart Cities - Eliminating Water Pollution |last=O'Brien |first=Sara Ashley |work=CNN Money|accessdate=13 November 2014|date=2014-11-11 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www1.villanova.edu/content/dam/villanova/engineering/vcase/sym-presentations/3a3_Making%20Green_Andrea%20Braga.pdf |title=Making Green Work, and Work Harder |last=Braga |first=Andrea |publisher=Geosyntec |pages=5 |accessdate=30 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nGenerally, [[check dam]]s are constructed across the streams to enhance the percolation of surface water into the [[subsoil]] strata. The water percolation in the water-impounded area of the check dams can be enhanced artificially manyfold by loosening the subsoil strata and [[overburden]] using [[ANFO]] explosives as used in [[open cast mining]]. Thus, local [[aquifer]]s can be recharged quickly using the available surface water fully for use in the dry season.\n\n=== Nontraditional ===\nIn 1992, American artist [[Michael Jones McKean]] created an artwork in Omaha, Nebraska, at the [[Bemis Center for Contemporary Art]] that created a fully sustainable rainbow in the Omaha skyline. The project collected thousands of gallons of rainwater, storing the water in six daisy-chained 12,000 gallons tanks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.therainbow.org/overview/|title=Archived copy|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131207115012/http://www.therainbow.org/overview/|archivedate=2013-12-07|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-12-17}}</ref> The massive logistical undertaking, during its five-month span, was one of the largest urban rainwater harvesting sites in the American Midwest.\n\n=== Rainwater harvesting by freshwater-flooded forests ===\n[[File:Ratargul, Sylhet.jpg|thumb|[[Ratargul Swamp Forest|Ratagul Freshwater Flooded Forest]], [[Bangladesh]]]]\nRainwater harvesting is possible by growing [[Freshwater swamp forest|freshwater-flooded forests]] without losing the income from the used, submerged land.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.scribd.com/document/58789361/Rain-Water-Harvesting-by-Freshwater-Flooded-Forests |title=Rain Water Harvesting by Freshwater Flooded Forests}}</ref> The main purpose of the rainwater harvesting is to use the locally available rainwater to meet water requirements throughout the year without the need of huge capital expenditure. This would facilitate the availability of uncontaminated water for domestic, industrial, and irrigation needs.\n\n=== Rainwater harvesting by solar power panels ===\nGood quality water resource, closer to populated areas, is becoming scarce and costly for the consumers. In addition to solar and wind energy, rain water is major [[renewable resource]] of any land. Vast area is being covered by [[Photovoltaics|solar PV panels]] every year in all parts of the world. Solar panels can also be used for harvesting most of the rain water falling on them and drinking quality water, free from bacteria and suspended matter, can be generated by simple [[Water purification|filtration and disinfection]] processes as rain water is very low in [[salinity]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.windpowerengineering.com/environmental/wind-solar-powered-offgridbox-useful-hurricane-passes/ |title=Rain fed solar powered water purification systems. |accessdate=21 October 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://cleantechnica.com/2017/12/04/inverted-umbrella-brings-clean-water-clean-power-india/ |title=Inverted Umbrella Brings Clean Water & Clean Power To India |accessdate=5 December 2017|date=2017-12-04 }}</ref><ref name=inh>{{cite web |url=https://inhabitat.com/new-rooftop-solar-hydropanels-harvest-drinking-water-and-energy-at-the-same-time/  |title=New rooftop solar hydro panels harvest drinking water and energy at the same time |accessdate=2017-11-30}}</ref> Exploitation of rain water for value added products like bottled drinking water, makes solar PV power plants profitable even in high rainfall/ cloudy areas by the augmented income from value added drinking water generation.\nRecently cost effective Rain water collection in the already dug wells found to be highly effective in the bringing ground water level up in India.\n\n== Advantages ==\nRainwater harvesting provides the independent water supply during regional water restrictions, and in developed countries, is often used to supplement the main supply. It provides water when a drought occurs, can help mitigate flooding of low-lying areas, and reduces demand on wells which may enable groundwater levels to be sustained. It also helps in the availability of potable water, as rainwater is substantially free of salinity and other salts. Applications of rainwater harvesting in [[Integrated urban water management|urban water system]] provides a substantial benefit for both [[water supply]] and [[wastewater]] subsystems by reducing the need for [[clean water]] in water distribution systems, less generated [[stormwater]] in [[sewer system]]s,<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Behzadian |first=k |last2=Kapelan |first2=Z |date=2015 |title=Advantages of integrated and sustainability based assessment for metabolism based strategic planning of urban water systems |journal=Science of the Total Environment |volume=527-528 |pages=220\u2013231 |doi=10.1016/j.scitotenv.2015.04.097 |pmid= 25965035|hdl=10871/17351 |url=https://ore.exeter.ac.uk/repository/bitstream/10871/17351/1/Behzadian%20and%20Kapelan%202015b.pdf |bibcode=2015ScTEn.527..220B }}</ref> and a reduction in stormwater runoff polluting freshwater bodies.\n\nA large body of work has focused on the development of life cycle assessment and its costing methodologies to assess the level of environmental impacts and money that can be saved by implementing rainwater harvesting systems.<ref name=inh/>\n\n=== Independent water supply ===\nRainwater harvesting provides an independent water supply during water restrictions. In areas where clean water is costly, or difficult to come by, rainwater harvesting is a critical source of clean water. In developed countries, rainwater is often harvested to be used as a supplemental source of water rather than the main source, but the harvesting of rainwater can also decrease a household's water costs or overall usage levels. Rainwater is safe to drink if the consumers do additional treatments before drinking. Boiling water helps to kill germs. Adding another supplement to the system such as a first flush diverter is also a common procedure to avoid contaminants of the water. <ref> Centers of Disease Control and Prevention (CDC), 2013 Retrieved from https://www.cdc.gov/healthywater/drinking/private/rainwater-collection.html </ref>\n\n=== Supplemental in drought ===\nWhen drought occurs, rainwater harvested in past months can be used. If rain is scarce but also unpredictable, the use of a rainwater harvesting system can be critical to capturing the rain when it does fall. Many countries with arid environments, use rainwater harvesting as a cheap and reliable source of clean water. To enhance irrigation in arid environments, ridges of soil are constructed to trap and prevent rainwater from running down hills. Even in periods of low [[rainfall]], enough water is collected for crops to grow. Water can be collected from roofs and tanks can be constructed to hold large quantities of rainwater.\n\nIn addition, rainwater harvesting decreases the demand for water from wells, enabling groundwater levels to be further sustained rather than depleted.\n\n=== Life-cycle assessment ===\n[[Life-cycle assessment]] is a methodology used to evaluate the environmental impacts of a system from cradle-to-grave of its lifetime. Devkota et al,<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Devkota |first1=J. |last2=Schlachter |first2=H. |last3=Anand |first3=C. |last4=Phillips |first4=R. |last5=Apul |first5=Defne |date=November 2013 |title=Development and application of EEAST: A lifecycle-based model for use of harvested rainwater and composting toilets in buildings |journal=Journal of Environmental Management |volume=130 |pages=397\u2013404 |doi=10.1016/j.jenvman.2013.09.015|pmid=24141064 }}</ref><ref name=\"Devkota 20152\">{{Cite journal |last1=Devkota |first1=Jay |last2=Schlachter |first2=Hannah |last3=Apul |first3=Defne |date=May 2015 |title=Life cycle based evaluation of harvested rainwater use in toilets and for irrigation |journal=Journal of Cleaner Production |volume=95 |pages=311\u2013321 |doi=10.1016/j.jclepro.2015.02.021}}</ref> developed such a methodology for rainwater harvesting, and found that the building design (e.g., dimensions) and function (e.g., educational, residential, etc.) play critical roles in the environmental performance of the system. The Economic and Environmental Analysis of Sanitations Technologies, [https://defneapul.wikispaces.com/Water+sustainability EEAST] model evaluates the greenhouse gas emissions and cost of such systems over the lifetime of a variety of building types.\n\nTo address the functional parameters of rainwater harvesting systems, a new metric was developed - the demand to supply ratio (D/S) - identifying the ideal building design (supply) and function (demand) in regard to the environmental performance of rainwater harvesting for toilet flushing. With the idea that supply of rainwater not only saves the potable water, but also saves the stormwater entering the combined sewer network (thereby requiring treatment), the savings in environmental emissions were higher if the buildings are connected to a combined sewer network compared to separate one.<ref name=\"Devkota 20152\"/>\n\n== System setup ==\n[[File:To Catch the Rain.pdf|thumb|''To Catch the Rain'', a 2017 book on rainwater harvesting]]\nRainwater harvesting systems can range in complexity, from systems that can be installed with minimal skills, to automated systems that require advanced setup and installation. The basic rainwater harvesting system is more of a plumbing job than a technical job, as all the outlets from the building's terrace are connected through a pipe to an underground tank that stores water.\n\nSystems are ideally sized to meet the water demand throughout the dry season, since it must be big enough to support daily water consumption. Specifically, the rainfall capturing area such as a building roof must be large enough to maintain adequate flow of water. The water storage tank size should be large enough to contain the captured water. \nFor low-tech systems, many low-tech methods are used to capture rainwater: rooftop systems, surface water capture and pumping the rainwater that has already soaked into the ground or captured in reservoirs and storing it in tanks (cisterns).\n\nBefore a rainwater harvesting system is built, use of digital tools is useful, for instance to detect if a region has a high rainwater harvesting potential or to estimate how much water is needed to fulfill a community's water needs. These tools can save time and money before a commitment to build a system is undertaken, in addition to making the project sustainable and long lasting.\n\n== Applications of rainwater harvesting ==\n=== Agriculture ===\n\nIn regards to [[Urban agriculture]] rainwater harvesting in urban areas reduces the impact of runoff and flooding. The combination of urban \u2018green\u2019 rooftops with rainwater catchments have been found to reduce building temperatures by more than 1.3 degrees Celsius.<ref name=\"Amos 174\u2013190\">{{Cite journal|last=Amos|first=Caleb Christian|last2=Rahman|first2=Ataur|last3=Karim|first3=Fazlul|last4=Gathenya|first4=John Mwangi|date=November 2018|title=A scoping review of roof harvested rainwater usage in urban agriculture: Australia and Kenya in focus|journal=Journal of Cleaner Production|volume=202|pages=174\u2013190|doi=10.1016/j.jclepro.2018.08.108|issn=0959-6526}}</ref> Rainwater harvesting in conjunction with urban agriculture would be a viable way to help meet the United Nations Sustainable Development Goals for cleaner and sustainable cities, health and wellbeing, and food and water security. The technology is available, however, needs to be remodeled in order to use water more efficiently, especially in an urban setting.\n\nKenya has already been successfully harvesting rainwater for toilets, laundry, and irrigation and areas in Australia use harvested rainwater for cooking and drinking.<ref name=\"Amos 174\u2013190\"/> Studies done by Stout et al researching the feasibility in India found RWH was most beneficial used for small scale irrigation, which provides income with the sales of produce,\u00a0and overflow used for groundwater recharge.<ref name=\"Amos 174\u2013190\"/>\n\nMissions to five Caribbean countries have shown that the capture and storage of rainwater runoff for later use is able to significantly reduce the risk of losing some or all of the year's harvest because of soil or water scarcity. In addition, the risks associated with flooding and soil erosion during high rainfall seasons would decrease. Small farmers, especially those farming on hillsides, could benefit the most from rainwater harvesting because they are able to capture runoff and decrease the effects of soil erosion.<ref name=\":83\">{{Cite journal |last=Fletcher-Paul |first=Dr. Lystra |date= |title=Feasibility Study of Rainwater Harvesting for Agriculture in the Caribbean Subregion |url=http://www.fao.org/3/a-bq747e.pdf |journal=FAO |volume= |pages= |via=}}</ref>\n\nMany countries, especially those with arid environments, use rainwater harvesting as a cheap and reliable source of clean water.<ref>{{Cite book |title=Rainwater Harvesting for Agriculture and Water Supply |last=Zhu |first=Qiang |publisher=Springer |year=2015 |isbn=978-981-287-964-6 |location=Beijing |pages=20 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> To enhance [[irrigation]] in arid environments, ridges of soil are constructed to trap and prevent rainwater from running down hills and slopes. Even in periods of low [[rainfall]], enough water is collected for crops to grow.<ref name=\":322\">{{Cite web |url=http://practicalaction.org/rainwater-harvesting-8 |title=Rainwater harvesting}}</ref> Water can be collected from roofs, dams and ponds can be constructed to hold large quantities of [[rain]]water so that even on days when little to no rainfall occurs, enough is available to irrigate crops.\n\n=== Domestic use ===\n* In China, Argentina, and Brazil, rooftop rainwater harvesting is used to provide drinking water, domestic water, water for livestock, water for small irrigation, and a way to replenish groundwater levels. [[Gansu]] province in China and semiarid [[Northeast Region, Brazil|northeast Brazil]] have the largest rooftop rainwater harvesting projects going on.\n* About 40% of Thailand's rural population utilizes rainwater harvesting.<ref name=\"JMP 2016\"/> Rainwater harvesting was promoted heavily by the government in the 1950s. In the 1990s, after government funding for the collection tanks ran out, the private sector stepped in and provided several million tanks to private households, many of which continue to be used today.<ref name=\"saladin20162\"/> This is one of the largest examples of [[Self-supply of water and sanitation|self-supply of water]] worldwide.\n* Rainwater harvesting is mandatory for new homes built in [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=SANTA FE COUNTY Ordinance No. 2003-6: An Ordinance Amending Ordinance 1996-10, the Santa Fe County Land Development Code, Article III, Section 4.4.1 and Article III, Section 2.4.1 to require rainwater catchment systems for all commercial and residential development. |last= |first= |year=2003 |isbn= |location= |pages=}}</ref>\n* [[Texas]] offers a sales tax exemption for the purchase of rainwater harvesting equipment.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.twdb.texas.gov/publications/shells/RainwaterHarvesting.pdf |title=Rainwater Harvesting |last=Texas Water Development Board |date=February 2018 |website=Water for Texas }}</ref>\n* Both Texas<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.capitol.state.tx.us/tlodocs/82R/billtext/html/HB03391F.htm |title=82(R) H.B. No. 3391. Act relating to rainwater harvesting and other water conservation initiatives. \u2020 went into effect on September 1, 2011 |work=82nd Regular Session |publisher=Texas Legislature Online |accessdate=8 February 2013}}</ref> and [[Ohio]] allow rainwater harvesting to be used even for potable purposes.\n* [[Oklahoma]] passed the Water for 2060 Act in 2012, to promote pilot projects for rainwater and [[graywater]] use among other water-saving techniques.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.owrb.ok.gov/2060/pdf/2014Waterfor2060factsheet.pdf |title=Water for 2060 Fact Sheet |last=Oklahoma Water Resources Board }}</ref>\n* In the [[United Kingdom]], [[Rainwater tank|water butts]] are often found in domestic gardens and on [[Allotment (gardening)|allotments]] to collect rainwater, which is then used to water the garden.\n\n=== Industry ===\nFrankfurt Airport has the biggest rainwater harvesting system in Germany. The system helps save approximately 1 million cubic meters of water per year. The cost of the system was 1.5 million dm (US$63,000) in 1993. This system collects water from roofs of the new terminal which has an area of 26,800 square metres. The water is collected in the basement of the airport in six tanks with a storage capacity of 100 cubic meters. The water is mainly used for toilet flushing, watering plants and cleaning the air conditioning system.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rainwaterharvesting.org/international/germany.htm |title=The Rainwater Harvesting System at Mira Model School |website=www.rainwaterharvesting.org |access-date=2018-04-24}}</ref>\n\nRainwater harvesting was adopted at The Velodrome \u2013 The [[Olympic Park, London|London Olympic Park]] \u2013 in order to increase the sustainability of the facility. A 73% decrease in potable water demand by the park was estimated. Despite this, it was deemed that rainwater harvesting was a less efficient use of financial resources to increase sustainability than the park's blackwater recycling program.<ref name=\":93\">{{Cite web |url=http://learninglegacy.independent.gov.uk/documents/pdfs/sustainability/154-rainwater-harvesting-sust.pdf |title=Learning legacy: Lessons learned from the London 2012 Games construction project |date=2011 |website=Olympic Delivery Authority }}</ref>\n\n== Quality of water harvesting ==\nRainwater may need to be analyzed properly, and used in a way appropriate to its safety. In the [[Gansu]] province for example, [[solar water disinfection]] is used by boiling harvested rainwater in parabolic solar cookers before being used for drinking.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://english.people.com.cn/90001/90781/6248934.html |last=Chen |first=Xuefei |title=Rainwater harvesting benefits farmers in Gansu |work=People's Daily Online |date=27 August 2007}}</ref> These so-called \"[[appropriate technology]]\" methods provide low-cost disinfection options for treatment of stored rainwater for drinking.\n\nWhile rainwater itself is a clean source of water, often better than groundwater or water from rivers or lakes,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hatch |first1=Jacob |title=The Many Benefits of Rainwater Harvesting |url=https://hydrationanywhere.com/the-many-benefits-of-rain-water-harvesting/ |website=Hydration Anywhere |publisher=Hydration Anywhere |accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref> the process of collection and storage often leaves the water polluted and non-potable. Rainwater harvested from roofs can contain human, animal and bird [[feces]], [[moss]]es and [[lichen]]s, windblown dust, particulates from urban pollution, pesticides, and inorganic [[ion]]s from the sea ([[Calcium|Ca]], [[Magnesium|Mg]], [[Sodium|Na]], [[Potassium|K]], [[Chlorine|Cl]], [[sulfate|SO<sub>4</sub>]]), and dissolved gases ([[carbon dioxide|CO<sub>2</sub>]], [[nitrogen oxide|NO<sub>x</sub>]], [[sulfur oxide|SO<sub>x</sub>]]). High levels of pesticide have been found in rainwater in Europe with the highest concentrations occurring in the first rain immediately after a dry spell;<ref>{{Cite magazine |last1=Pearce |first1=Fred |last2=Mackenzie |first2=Debora |date=3 April 1999 |title=It's raining pesticides |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/mg16221803-100-its-raining-pesticides/ |magazine=New Scientist |issue=2180 |access-date=10 July 2018}}</ref> the concentration of these and other contaminants are reduced significantly by diverting the [[First flush|initial flow]] of run-off water to waste. Improved water quality can also be obtained by using a floating draw-off mechanism (rather than from the base of the tank) and by using a series of tanks, withdraw from the last in series. Prefiltration is a common practice used in the industry to keep the system healthy and ensure that the water entering the tank is free of large sediments.\n\nA very interesting concept of rain water harvesting and cleaning it with solar energy for rural household drinking purposes has been developed by [[Nimbkar Agricultural Research Institute]]. <ref>[https://www.currentscience.ac.in/Volumes/118/06/0872.pdf Low cost drinking water technology \u2013 rainwater harvesting with solar purification. Current Science, Vol. 118, No.6, 25 March 2020]</ref>\n\nConceptually, a water supply system should match the quality of water with the end use. However, in most of the developed world, high-quality potable water is used for all end uses. This approach wastes money and energy and imposes unnecessary impacts to the environment. Supplying rainwater that has gone through preliminary filtration measures for nonpotable water uses, such as toilet flushing, irrigation and laundry, may be a significant part of a sustainable water management strategy.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Ecology}}\n* {{annotated link|Air well (condenser)}}\n* {{annotated link|Atmospheric water generator}} \n* {{annotated link|Deepwater rice}}\n* {{annotated link|Detention basin}} \n* {{annotated link|Peak water}} \n* {{annotated link|Retention basin}}\n* {{annotated link|Water conservation}}\n* [https://www.schoolproject.in/working-model-of-rainwater-harvesting-for-school-project/ DIY Rainwater Harvesting Project for students]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|35em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Sister project links | wikt=no | n=no | q=no | s=no |v=no}}\n{{Wikiversity}}\n\n[[Category:Rainwater harvesting|*]]\n[[Category:Water supply]]\n[[Category:Water conservation]]\n[[Category:Irrigation]]\n[[Category:Appropriate technology]]\n[[Category:Hydrology and urban planning]]\n[[Category:DIY culture]]\n[[Category:Aquifers]]\n[[Category:Sustainable gardening]]\n", "name_user": "Tanvir Sahu", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory of rain water harvesting", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rainwater_harvesting"}
{"title_page": "Baru Bian", "text_new": "{{short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Tuan]]\n| name = Baru Bian\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| image        = \n| image_size   = \n| office = [[Minister of Works (Malaysia)|Minister of Works]]\n[[File:BaruBian2.jpg|thumb|Key Note Address by YB Baru Bian]]\n| monarch = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| primeminister =[[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| constituency     = [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]]\n| term_start       = 2 July 2018\n| term_end         = 24 February 2020\n| deputy           = [[Mohd Anuar Mohd Tahir]]\n| \n|  \n| predecessor      = [[Fadillah Yusof]]\n| successor        = [[Fadillah Yusof]]\n| office2 = Chairman of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (Sarawak)\n| term_start2 = 2009\n| term_end2 = 2020\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 =\n| constituency_MP3 = [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]], [[Sarawak]]\n| parliament3 = Malaysian\n| majority3 = 486 ([[Malaysian general election, 2018|2018]])\n| term_start3 = 10 May 2018\n| term_end3 =\n| predecessor3 = [[Joseph Entulu Belaun]]\n| successor3 =\n| office4 =\n| term_start4 = 16 April 2011\n| term_end4 =\n| predecessor4 = Nelson Balang Rining\n| successor4 =\n| majority4 = 473 ([[Sarawak state election, 2011|2011]]) <br /> 538 ([[Sarawak state election, 2016|2016]])\n| assembly4 = Sarawak State Legislative\n| constituency_AM4 = [[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|09|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lawas]], [[Crown Colony of Sarawak]] {{small|(now [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]]}}\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = {{MAS}}\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak|Sarawak Native People's Party]] (PBDS) {{small|(1987-2004)}}<br/> [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) {{small|(2008-2020)}}<br/> [[Independent politician|Independent]]<ref>[https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/11/baru-bian-clarifies-he-has-not-joined-bersatu-is-an-independent-mp/1845483 I am not joining BERSATU]</ref> {{small|(2020-now)}}\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] {{small|(2008-2015)}}<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) {{small|(2015-2020)}}<br /> [[Perikatan Nasional]] (PN)\n| alma_mater = [[Universiti Teknologi MARA]]<br />[[University of Melbourne]]\n| spouse = Yu Ching Sieu\n| children =\n| occupation = Politician<br />Lawyer\n| relations =\n| website = {{URL|http://www.barubian.net/}}\n| footnotes =\n|}}\n\n\n'''Baru Bian''' (born 9 September 1958) is a [[Malaysians|Malaysian]] [[politician]]. He is the member of parliament of [[Selangau]] winning in 2018 Malaysia General Election. He is formerly the Sarawak Chief of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party (PKR)]] in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] governing coalition formerly serving as the [[Minister of Works (Malaysia)|Minister of Works]] of [[Malaysia]]. \n\nHe created history when he became the first leader of the [[Lun Bawang]] community to be appointed as a [[cabinet minister]].<ref name=\"history\">{{cite news |title=Baru Bian creates history |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/07/03/baru-bian-creates-history/ |accessdate=20 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=3 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704025517/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/07/03/baru-bian-creates-history/ |archivedate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n\n[[File:BaruBian5.jpg|thumb|Attending Community Event]]\n\n\n==Early life and career==\nBaru Bian was born in an impoverished [[Lun Bawang]] family on 9 September 1958,<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> to Bian Labo (father) and Takong Taie (mother) in [[Long Lopeng]], [[Sarawak]].<ref name=\"Awakening\">{{cite book |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |last2=Deborah |first2=Loh |title=The Long Awakening |date=2014 |publisher=Baru Bian |location=Kuching, Sarawak |isbn=978-967-12316-0-9 |language=English}}</ref><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages iii, and i.v</ref> The ancestry of Baru Bian can be traced back to Berunut area, near the Adang river, where the latter is the tributary of the [[Limbang River]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 38</ref> All the genuine Lun Bawang people should be able to trace their ancestry to one single common ancestor named Terur Aco. Baru Bian and his siblings are the twentieth generation since the first Lun Bawang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 40</ref>  He is the third child and the eldest son in the family. He has six siblings. His elder sisters are Mina and Serina. Freddie is his younger brother, followed by a sister named Sigang, a brother Paulus, and another sister named Litad.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Both Baru's parents were pastors.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> Baru's father, Bian Labo was trained at [[Lawas]] bible school which was under the [[Sidang Injil Borneo]] (SIB) church.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Baru's family moved from one village to another because his father was posted to different villages every year.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Brought up in a Christian family since childhood, Baru was taught of discipline and doing the right things by his father.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> \n\n\nBaru met his current wife Ching Sieu during his studies at Melbourne, Australia when he joined Overseas Christian Fellowship (OCF).<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 31</ref> Baru returned to Malaysia after graduation in 1986, Ching Sieu was still studying for another year for her double degree. She only returned to Malaysia in 1987. Baru and Ching Sieu was married on 17 December 1988.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 146</ref> Baru and Ching Sieu raised three children, all three are now practicing Lawyers.<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> Meanwhile, Ching Sieu is a full-time housewife.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 223</ref>\n\nBaru's father died of stomach cancer in 1993 at the age of 62 and was buried at Miri.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 38</ref>\n\n===Education===\nBy the age of seven or eight, he followed his father into the jungle to learn hunting and fishing. As he became older, he would learn jungle survival skills, geography and boundary of the ancestral lands, and memorise twenty generations of ancestral names.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 14</ref> He attended Primary 1 to 2 at Long Lellang (1966 to 1967), Primary 3 to 4 at Long Semado (1968-1969), and passed common entrance examination at Long Napir (1970 to 1971).<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\">{{cite web |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |title=Curriculum vitae |url=http://www.barubian.net/p/curriculum-vitae.html |publisher=barubian.net |accessdate=1 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218132510/http://www.barubian.net/p/curriculum-vitae.html |archivedate=18 February 2018}}</ref> After that, he attended Limbang secondary school until Form 5.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 12</ref> At one point, he would need to wear modified school blouse left by her sister for the secondary school.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 13</ref> He need to hike in the jungles for three days before reaching [[Lawas]] and another day journey to reach [[Limbang]].<ref name=\"Fighter\">{{cite news |last1=Sharon |first1=Ling |title=A fighter with big dreams |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/29/a-fighter-with-big-dreams-from-the-courts-to-the-august-house-this-native-land-rights-lawyer-turned/ |accessdate=20 November 2018 |publisher=The Star (Malaysia) |date=29 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729030515/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/29/a-fighter-with-big-dreams-from-the-courts-to-the-august-house-this-native-land-rights-lawyer-turned/ |archivedate=29 July 2018}}</ref> His experiences during journeys through the jungles and mountain streams led him to understand the value of [[Aboriginal title#Malaysia|Native Customary Rights]] (NCR) for ''pemakai menoa'' (territorial domain) and ''pulau galau'' (communal forest reserve) and also the environmental protection.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> During the year-end school holidays in 1980, Baru Bian interviewed his father and his uncle Lasong Labo about the history of their family's NCR land. He drew the boundaries of their NCR land and signed by the village headman. The map later proved to be useful in fighting against six logging companies encroaching their lands in Berunut from 1986 to 1990s.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 15, 105-116</ref>\n\nHe attended Kolej Tun Datu Tuanku Haji Bujang for Form 6 at Tanjong Lobang, [[Miri]], Sarawak. He got a satisfactory result in [[GCE Ordinary Level]] examination.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 12, 24</ref> After completing his secondary education, he served as a temporary teacher at SMK Medamit, [[Limbang]] from 1979 to 1981. He taught Geography, History, Physical Education and General Science there.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 25</ref><ref name=\"history\"/> His passion towards native land rights had led him pursued his tertiary education at Institut Teknology Mara (ITM) (now [[Universiti Teknologi MARA]] (UiTM)), [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]] in Diploma in Law (DIL).<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> His uncle, Libat Langub, who was a former student at ITM, encouraged him to study law there.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 25</ref> He went to Melbourne to further his studies on Law in 1985.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 31</ref> He applied for scholarship from ITM but was denied. Therefore, he decided to take a study loan instead.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 28</ref> He subsequently obtained [[Bachelor of Laws|Bachelor of Laws (LL.B)]] from the [[University of Melbourne]], [[Australia]] in 1986.<ref name=\"history\"/> After his graduation in Australia, Baru decided to come back to Malaysia to serve the needy instead of applying for permanent residency in Australia.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 145</ref>\n\n===Law career===\nUpon graduation, he became a trainee in a law firm named Rashid & Lee in [[Kuala Lumpur]] for six months before the law firm stopped paying allowances due to financial difficulties. He then continued his training at Eddy Chung & Co and was employed there until he returned to Kuching in 1988.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 146</ref> Baru was subsequently admitted to the [[Malaysian Bar|Malayan Bar]] as a lawyer and [[solicitor]].<ref name=\"history\"/> By 1990, Baru became a partner in the firm of Messrs Anthony Ting, Baru Bian & Co. in Kuching, Sarawak.<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> Baru taught himself about native customary rights law through Sahabat Alam Malaysia (SAM), an NGO led by [[Harrison Ngau Laing]], an environmentalist. Baru would later became a legal advisor for SAM.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 147</ref> In the same year, he represented SAM to [[Yokohama]], [[Japan]] to protest against the [[International Tropical Timber Organization]] (ITTO) for not including the issues of native customary rights in their report. It was also at this time that Baru Bian met the Swiss activist, [[Bruno Manser]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 147</ref> Bruno would later helped Baru to raise RM 30,000 from overseas supporters to fund Baru's [[1991 Sarawak state election|1991 election]] endeavour.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 148</ref> However, Malaysian embassy officials would later took a photo of Baru Bian and Bruno Manser in Yokohama and used the photo to depict Baru as a traitor to Malaysian interests in 1991 election.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 151</ref>\n\nBaru filed his first NCR case in 1991 on behalf of his extended family whose ancestral lands in Berunut was encroached by logging companies. However, the case was pending in court after two years. Therefore, Baru and his family members took part in timber blockades which successfully led Samling (a logging company) to compensate them RM 100,000. As part of the agreement, Baru withdrew the court case.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 105-116</ref><ref name=\"Fighter\"/> He set up Messrs Baru Bian Advocates and Solicitors in [[Kuching]] in 1992.<ref name=\"history\"/> Baru would later found a legal partner named See Chee How. See is a human rights activist and a lawyer from Kuching. Together, they were involved in numerous native land rights cases.<ref name=\"Money Logging\"/> Baru also took up cases related to wrongful arrests or jailed without [[Remand (detention)|remand]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 119-120</ref> In 2001, Baru Bian won the Rumah Nor Nyawai case in Sarawak High Court. This was the first time in the history of Malaysian courts that NCR rights was upheld.<ref name=\"Money Logging\">{{cite book |last1=Lukas |first1=Straumann |title=Money Logging On the Trail of the Asian Timber Mafia |date=2014 |publisher=[[Bergli Books]] |location=Basel, Switzerland |isbn=978-3-905252-72-9 |pages=205 |edition=First |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-F8aCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT205&lpg=PT205&dq=Rumah+Nor+case+Baru+Bian&source=bl&ots=4zYK2xKiqv&sig=Qr2nH7ho0bjG07J476ClvMBtxow&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi7puTQw_DeAhUKKo8KHeyJC9EQ6AEwC3oECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Rumah%20Nor%20case%20Baru%20Bian&f=false |accessdate=2 November 2018 |language=English |chapter= Chapter 6 -  Bruno Manser's legacy}}</ref> In 2007, the [[Federal Court of Malaysia]] upheld the decision on Rumah Nor Nyawai case that ''pemakai menua'' and ''pulau galau'', in addition to ''temuda'' (cultivated land before 1 January 1958) are included in the definition of NCR land.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 128</ref> In March 2011, Baru successfully led the legal defence team consisting of Civil Rights Lawyers See Chee How & Desmond Kho, resulting in the acquittal of Numpang Suntai who was accused of burning ten items of machinery in a logging camp at Sebangan, [[Simunjan District]] for encroaching the latter's ancestral land.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 120</ref> By 2013, Baru Bian's law firm had processed more than 200 native land rights cases in court.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 131</ref>\n\nBaru Bian's belief in the freedom of religion guaranteed by the [[Constitution of Malaysia]] had prompted him to take up cases for those who wished to leave the religion of Islam.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |title=Baru Bian: Court of Appeal Decision a Letdown for converts out of Islam |url=https://www.borneotoday.net/baru-bian-court-of-appeal-decision-a-letdown-for-converts-out-of-islam/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |agency=Press statement |publisher=Borneo Today |date=12 November 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117020750/https://www.borneotoday.net/baru-bian-court-of-appeal-decision-a-letdown-for-converts-out-of-islam/ |archivedate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wanita Melayu Diwakili Peguam Baru Bian Gagal Dalam Rayuan Kes Murtad (A Malay lady who was represented by lawyer Baru Bian lost the appeal in an apostasy case) |url=https://www.menara.my/wanita-melayu-diwakili-peguam-baru-bian-gagal-dalam-rayuan-kes-murtad/ |publisher=menara.my |accessdate=23 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223124445/https://www.menara.my/wanita-melayu-diwakili-peguam-baru-bian-gagal-dalam-rayuan-kes-murtad/ |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Law is silent on Muslim converts wishing to leave Islam \u2013 Baru |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=11 February 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330175031/http://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/ |archivedate=30 March 2018}}</ref> His representations in the [[apostasy]] cases has drawn criticisms from [[Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS), accusing him of contempt against the Islamic religion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru Bian blasts death threats, insults over apostasy case |url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2018/02/28/baru-bian-blasts-death-threats-insults-over-apostasy-case/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Free Malaysia Today |date=28 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Baru Bian hina umat Islam Sarawak' (Baru Bian insulted Islam in Sarawak) |url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/413661 |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Malaysiakini |date=27 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223132425/https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/413661 |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kamarul |first1=Zaman Yusoff |title=Baru Bian juara Kristianisasi Sarawak (Baru Bian is the champion of christianisation in Sarawak) |url=http://www.harakahdaily.net/index.php/berita/15-tanah-air/5501-baru-bian-juara-kristianisasi-sarawak |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Harakah Daily |date=28 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403152628/http://www.harakahdaily.net/index.php/berita/15-tanah-air/5501-baru-bian-juara-kristianisasi-sarawak |archivedate=3 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1987, Baru joined [[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak]] (PBDS) because the party was advocating NCR rights in Sarawak.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 1989, Baru was elected as PBDS Youth Executive Council member.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 171</ref> Baru was also a supreme council member of PBDS.<ref name=\"history\"/> He first contested against Sarawak [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) governing coalition at [[Lawas (state constituency)|Lawas]] in 1991 but lost. After that, PBDS started negotiating to rejoin Sarawak BN in 1992 and was subsequently admitted into BN in 1994.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oorjitham|first1=Santha|title=Dayak welfare was his priority|url=http://www2.nst.com.my/nation/general/dayak-welfare-was-his-priority-1.355519|accessdate=17 May 2015|publisher=New Straits Times|date=14 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920085822/http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/dayak-welfare-was-his-priority-1.355519|archivedate=20 September 2013 }}</ref> One of the condition for PBDS to rejoin BN was to stop raising the NCR issues within the state government. However, Baru Bian decided to continue his pursue towards NCR rights cases in court.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 2004, Baru decided to quit PBDS and went to contest against BN in [[2004 Ba'kelalan by-election|Ba'kelalan by-election]] as an independent but lost again. Baru believed in continuing to uphold the NCR lands among the natives and the need to change the Sarawak state government in order to solve the NCR problems permanently.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> Baru later joined [[Malaysian Dayak Congress]] (MDS). However, MDS did not get registered before [[2006 Sarawak state election]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 184</ref> Therefore, Baru contested again for [[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]] under [[Sarawak National Party]] (SNAP) ticket and lost for the third time. He filed an election petition to [[Miri, Malaysia|Miri]] High Court on BN's vote buying activities in Ba'kelalan. However, the petition was struck out on technicality grounds.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 192-193</ref> He then decided to retire from politics because he already lost three times in elections.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/>\n\nHowever, when BN lost its two-thirds majority in the parliament and five states to the opposition during the [[2008 Malaysian general election]], Baru decided to join politics again to strengthen the two-party system. He joined [[Parti Keadilan Rakyat]] (PKR) in the same year.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 2009, Baru was appointed as the chairman of PKR Sarawak.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> He then proceed to win the Ba'kelalan state constituency during [[2011 Sarawak state election]], having defeated the candidate for the BN coalition, Willie Liau, who is also his nephew, by a narrow 473-vote majority.<ref>{{cite news |title=I\u2019m still a winnable candidate in Ba\u2019 Kelalan \u2014 Balang |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/07/22/im-still-a-winnable-candidate-in-ba-kelalan-balang/ |accessdate=1 December 2018 |date=22 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714172227/http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/07/22/im-still-a-winnable-candidate-in-ba-kelalan-balang/ |archivedate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=William |first1=Mangor |title=Baru Bian: Sarawakians want to see changes |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2015/07/23/baru-bian-sarawakians-want-to-see-changes/ |accessdate=1 December 2018 |publisher=Free Malaysia Today |date=23 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065656/http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2015/07/23/baru-bian-sarawakians-want-to-see-changes/ |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Sarawak chief minister [[Adenan Satem]] invited Baru Bian to join BN, however, Baru declined the offer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Philip |first1=Kiew |title=\u2018Join BN, Baru Bian\u2019 |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/05/31/join-bn-baru-bian/ |accessdate=26 January 2019 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=31 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618235255/http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/05/31/join-bn-baru-bian/ |archivedate=18 June 2018}}</ref> Baru retained the seat in the [[2016 Sarawak state election]] with an increased majority of 538 votes, also against Willie.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sarawak Polls: Baru Bian retains Ba'kelalan seat |url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/05/144278/sarawak-polls-baru-bian-retains-bakelalan-seat |accessdate=26 November 2018 |agency=New Straits Times |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508124142/https://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/05/144278/sarawak-polls-baru-bian-retains-bakelalan-seat |archivedate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2013 Malaysian general election]], Baru Bian decided to contest in [[Limbang (federal constituency)|Limbang]] parliamentary seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru confirms standing in Limbang |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/03/09/baru-confirms-standing-in-limbang/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=9 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223223450/http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/03/09/baru-confirms-standing-in-limbang/ |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref> However, he was defeated by a huge margin against BN.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru admits stunned by a huge margin |url=https://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-borneo-post/20130507/281930245490336 |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=7 March 2013}}</ref>\nDuring the [[2018 Malaysian general election]], NCR issues at [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]] prompt Baru to contest for the seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=NCR issues prompted me to stand in Selangau \u2013 Baru |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/04/29/ncr-issues-prompted-me-to-stand-in-selangau-baru/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=29 April 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430002606/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/04/29/ncr-issues-prompted-me-to-stand-in-selangau-baru/ |archivedate=30 April 2018}}</ref> He subsequently won the parliamentary seat against BN's Rita Sarimah with a majority of 486 votes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jane |first1=Moh |title=Baru Bian secures maiden parliament win in Selangau |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/05/10/baru-bian-secures-maiden-parliament-win-in-selangau/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=10 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510000120/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/05/10/baru-bian-secures-maiden-parliament-win-in-selangau/ |archivedate=10 May 2018}}</ref> On 2 July 2018, Baru was sworn-in as the Minister of Works of Malaysia at [[Istana Negara, Jalan Tuanku Abdul Halim|National Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andrew |first1=Sia |title=Baru Bian, the first Lun Bawang minister, fought hard for Sarawak natives' land rights |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/baru-bian-first-lun-bawang-minister/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Star (Malaysia) |date=2 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703133337/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/baru-bian-first-lun-bawang-minister/ |archivedate=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New members of Malaysia's Cabinet sworn in |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/new-memebrs-of-malaysias-cabinet-sworn-in |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911082355/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/new-memebrs-of-malaysias-cabinet-sworn-in |archivedate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, he and 10 others Member of Parliament lead by [[Mohamed Azmin Ali]] decided to leave [[People's Justice Party, Malaysia|PKR]] and decided to support [[BERSATU]] Prime Minister candidate [[Mahathir Mohamad]] to remain as the Prime Minister. However [[Mahathir Mohamad]] refuse returning as the Prime Minister of Malaysia so [[BERSATU]] nominated [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] as the nominee for the Prime Minister position. After [[PH]] change their support from [[Anwar Ibrahim]] to [[Mahathir Mohamad]] as the Prime Minister, he (Baru Bian) and Jonathan Yasin who are the 11 MP's who's leaving [[People's Justice Party, Malaysia|PKR]] came back supporting [[Mahathir Mohamad]] as the Prime Minister rather than [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]. [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] make a disgusting move by giving an executive position to Jonathan Yasin in his new back-door government. It is said that he (Baru Bian) and 10 others ex-PKR MP's are officially a member of [[BERSATU]].\n\n==Hobbies and interests==\nBaru learned ''Ngajat'' dance during his primary school years at Long Lellang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 11</ref> Baru is able to sing songs in [[alto]] since he was in Form 4.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 3</ref> Baru started to play football while he was in Form 6.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 24</ref>\n\n[[File:BaruBian4.jpg|thumb|Encouraging Youth]]\n\n==Religion==\nBaru was baptised at [[Limbang River]] in 1973 by a New Zealand missionary named Murray Munroe.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> A few months before baptism, a testimony given by a former gangster from Singapore during an Inter-School Christian Fellowship (ISCF) meeting had strengthen Baru's belief in Christianity.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> Baru started to play guitar for Christian songs while he was a member of ISCF at SMK Limbang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> He later become the president of ICSF during Form 4 and Form 5. He participated in Young Christian Students Movement (YCSM) year-end mission trips during his secondary school years.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 20-22</ref> During his years at ITM, he attended Full Gospel Assembly Church service at Old Klang Road.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 29</ref> He also attended a Christian Fellowship in ITM.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 28</ref> When Baru studied at Melbourne, Australia, he attended Overseas Christian Fellowship (OCF).<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 31</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|[[1991 Sarawak state election|1991]]\n|'''[[Lawas (state constituency)|Lawas]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak|PBDS]])\n|align=\"right\" |2,433\n|28.59%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Tengah Ali Hassin''' ([[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|'''PBB''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''6,076'''\n|'''71.41%'''\n|8,619\n|3,643\n|74.10%\n|-\n|[[2004 Ba'kelalan by-election|2004]]\n|rowspan=4|'''[[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,391\n|32.85%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Nelson Balang Rining''' ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|'''SPDP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''2,843'''\n|'''67.15%'''\n|4,313\n|1,452\n|56.04%\n|-\n|[[2006 Sarawak state election|2006]]\n|{td bgcolor=\"#717190\"}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Sarawak National Party|SNAP]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,589\n|43.50%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Nelson Balang Rining''' ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|'''SPDP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''2,064'''\n|'''56.50%'''\n|3,680\n|475\n|58.56%\n|-\n|[[2011 Sarawak state election|2011]]\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Baru Bian'''}} ([[Parti Keadilan Rakyat|'''PKR''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''2,505'''\n|'''55.21%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Willie Liau ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|SPDP]])\n|align=\"right\" |2,032\n|44.79%\n|4,585\n|473\n|65.90%\n|-\n|[[2016 Sarawak state election|2016]]\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Baru Bian'''}} ([[Parti Keadilan Rakyat|'''PKR''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''2,858'''\n|'''55.20%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Willie Liau ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|SPDP]])\n|align=\"right\" |2,320\n|44.80%\n|5,229\n|538\n|70.90%\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Dewan Rakyat|Parliament of Malaysia]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|[[2013 Malaysian general election|2013]]\n|'''[[Limbang (federal constituency)|Limbang]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Parti Keadilan Rakyat|PKR]])\n|align=\"right\" |4,698\n|26.55%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''[[Hasbi Habibollah]]''' ([[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|'''PBB''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''12,999'''\n|'''73.45%'''\n|17,912\n|8,301\n|73.78%\n|-\n|[[2018 Malaysian general election|2018]]\n|'''[[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Keadilan}} |\n|{{nowrap|'''Baru Bian'''}} ([[Parti Keadilan Rakyat|'''PKR''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''11,228'''\n|'''51.11%'''\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|Rita Sarimah ([[Parti Rakyat Sarawak|PRS]])\n|align=\"right\" |10,742\n|48.89%\n|22,352\n|486\n|74.44%\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n{{Malaysian Ministers}}\n{{Sarawak-FedRep}}\n{{Seventh Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Pakatan Harapan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bian, Baru}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:University of Melbourne alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Christians]]\n[[Category:Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak politicians]]\n[[Category:Sarawak politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Justice Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Malaysian politician}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[Malay titles#Honorary styles|Yang Berhormat]] [[Malay titles#Other titles|Tuan]]\n| name = Baru Bian\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament|MP]], [[Member of the Legislative Assembly|MLA]]\n| image        = \n| image_size   = \n| office = [[Minister of Works (Malaysia)|Minister of Works]]\n[[File:BaruBian2.jpg|thumb|Key Note Address by YB Baru Bian]]\n| monarch = [[Muhammad V of Kelantan|Muhammad V]]<br/>[[Abdullah of Pahang|Abdullah]]\n| primeminister =[[Mahathir Mohamad]]\n| constituency     = [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]]\n| term_start       = 2 July 2018\n| term_end         = 24 February 2020\n| deputy           = [[Mohd Anuar Mohd Tahir]]\n| \n|  \n| predecessor      = [[Fadillah Yusof]]\n| successor        = [[Fadillah Yusof]]\n| office2 = Chairman of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (Sarawak)\n| term_start2 = 2009\n| term_end2 = 2020\n| predecessor2 = \n| successor2 =\n| constituency_MP3 = [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]], [[Sarawak]]\n| parliament3 = Malaysian\n| majority3 = 486 ([[Malaysian general election, 2018|2018]])\n| term_start3 = 10 May 2018\n| term_end3 =\n| predecessor3 = [[Joseph Entulu Belaun]]\n| successor3 =\n| office4 =\n| term_start4 = 16 April 2011\n| term_end4 =\n| predecessor4 = Nelson Balang Rining\n| successor4 =\n| majority4 = 473 ([[Sarawak state election, 2011|2011]]) <br /> 538 ([[Sarawak state election, 2016|2016]])\n| assembly4 = Sarawak State Legislative\n| constituency_AM4 = [[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]]\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|09|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Lawas]], [[Crown Colony of Sarawak]] {{small|(now [[Sarawak]], [[Malaysia]]}}\n| residence =\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = {{MAS}}\n| citizenship = [[Malaysian people|Malaysian]]\n| party = [[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak|Sarawak Native People's Party]] (PBDS) {{small|(1987-2004)}}<br/> [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party]] (PKR) {{small|(2008-2020)}}<br/> [[Independent politician|Independent]]<ref>[https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/03/11/baru-bian-clarifies-he-has-not-joined-bersatu-is-an-independent-mp/1845483 I am not joining BERSATU]</ref> {{small|(2020-now)}}\n| otherparty = [[Pakatan Rakyat]] {{small|(2008-2015)}}<br />[[Pakatan Harapan]] (PH) {{small|(2015-2020)}}<br /> [[Perikatan Nasional]] (PN)\n| alma_mater = [[Universiti Teknologi MARA]]<br />[[University of Melbourne]]\n| spouse = Yu Ching Sieu\n| children =\n| occupation = Politician<br />Lawyer\n| relations =\n| website = {{URL|http://www.barubian.net/}}\n| footnotes =\n|}}\n\n\n'''Baru Bian''' (born 9 September 1958) is a [[Malaysians|Malaysian]] [[politician]]. He is the member of parliament of [[Selangau]] winning in 2018 Malaysia General Election. He is formerly the Sarawak Chief of [[People's Justice Party (Malaysia)|People's Justice Party (PKR)]] in the [[Pakatan Harapan]] governing coalition formerly serving as the [[Minister of Works (Malaysia)|Minister of Works]] of [[Malaysia]]. \n\nHe created history when he became the first leader of the [[Lun Bawang]] community to be appointed as a [[cabinet minister]].<ref name=\"history\">{{cite news |title=Baru Bian creates history |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/07/03/baru-bian-creates-history/ |accessdate=20 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=3 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180704025517/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/07/03/baru-bian-creates-history/ |archivedate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n\n[[File:BaruBian5.jpg|thumb|Attending Community Event]]\n\n\n==Early life and career==\nBaru Bian was born in an impoverished [[Lun Bawang]] family on 9 September 1958,<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> to Bian Labo (father) and Takong Taie (mother) in [[Long Lopeng]], [[Sarawak]].<ref name=\"Awakening\">{{cite book |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |last2=Deborah |first2=Loh |title=The Long Awakening |date=2014 |publisher=Baru Bian |location=Kuching, Sarawak |isbn=978-967-12316-0-9 |language=English}}</ref><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages iii, and i.v</ref> The ancestry of Baru Bian can be traced back to Berunut area, near the Adang river, where the latter is the tributary of the [[Limbang River]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 38</ref> All the genuine Lun Bawang people should be able to trace their ancestry to one single common ancestor named Terur Aco. Baru Bian and his siblings are the twentieth generation since the first Lun Bawang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 40</ref>  He is the third child and the eldest son in the family. He has six siblings. His elder sisters are Mina and Serina. Freddie is his younger brother, followed by a sister named Sigang, a brother Paulus, and another sister named Litad.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Both Baru's parents were pastors.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> Baru's father, Bian Labo was trained at [[Lawas]] bible school which was under the [[Sidang Injil Borneo]] (SIB) church.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Baru's family moved from one village to another because his father was posted to different villages every year.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 10</ref> Brought up in a Christian family since childhood, Baru was taught of discipline and doing the right things by his father.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> \n\n\nBaru met his current wife Ching Sieu during his studies at Melbourne, Australia when he joined Overseas Christian Fellowship (OCF).<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 31</ref> Baru returned to Malaysia after graduation in 1986, Ching Sieu was still studying for another year for her double degree. She only returned to Malaysia in 1987. Baru and Ching Sieu was married on 17 December 1988.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 146</ref> Baru and Ching Sieu raised three children, all three are now practicing Lawyers.<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> Meanwhile, Ching Sieu is a full-time housewife.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 223</ref>\n\nBaru's father died of stomach cancer in 1993 at the age of 62 and was buried at Miri.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 38</ref>\n\n===Education===\nBy the age of seven or eight, he followed his father into the jungle to learn hunting and fishing. As he became older, he would learn jungle survival skills, geography and boundary of the ancestral lands, and memorise twenty generations of ancestral names.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 14</ref> He attended Primary 1 to 2 at Long Lellang (1966 to 1967), Primary 3 to 4 at Long Semado (1968-1969), and passed common entrance examination at Long Napir (1970 to 1971).<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\">{{cite web |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |title=Curriculum vitae |url=http://www.barubian.net/p/curriculum-vitae.html |publisher=barubian.net |accessdate=1 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180218132510/http://www.barubian.net/p/curriculum-vitae.html |archivedate=18 February 2018}}</ref> After that, he attended Limbang secondary school until Form 5.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 12</ref> At one point, he would need to wear modified school blouse left by her sister for the secondary school.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 13</ref> He need to hike in the jungles for three days before reaching [[Lawas]] and another day journey to reach [[Limbang]].<ref name=\"Fighter\">{{cite news |last1=Sharon |first1=Ling |title=A fighter with big dreams |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/29/a-fighter-with-big-dreams-from-the-courts-to-the-august-house-this-native-land-rights-lawyer-turned/ |accessdate=20 November 2018 |publisher=The Star (Malaysia) |date=29 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180729030515/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/29/a-fighter-with-big-dreams-from-the-courts-to-the-august-house-this-native-land-rights-lawyer-turned/ |archivedate=29 July 2018}}</ref> His experiences during journeys through the jungles and mountain streams led him to understand the value of [[Aboriginal title#Malaysia|Native Customary Rights]] (NCR) for ''pemakai menoa'' (territorial domain) and ''pulau galau'' (communal forest reserve) and also the environmental protection.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> During the year-end school holidays in 1980, Baru Bian interviewed his father and his uncle Lasong Labo about the history of their family's NCR land. He drew the boundaries of their NCR land and signed by the village headman. The map later proved to be useful in fighting against six logging companies encroaching their lands in Berunut from 1986 to 1990s.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 15, 105-116</ref>\n\nHe attended Kolej Tun Datu Tuanku Haji Bujang for Form 6 at Tanjong Lobang, [[Miri]], Sarawak. He got a satisfactory result in [[GCE Ordinary Level]] examination.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 12, 24</ref> After completing his secondary education, he served as a temporary teacher at SMK Medamit, [[Limbang]] from 1979 to 1981. He taught Geography, History, Physical Education and General Science there.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 25</ref><ref name=\"history\"/> His passion towards native land rights had led him pursued his tertiary education at Institut Teknology Mara (ITM) (now [[Universiti Teknologi MARA]] (UiTM)), [[Shah Alam]], [[Selangor]] in Diploma in Law (DIL).<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> His uncle, Libat Langub, who was a former student at ITM, encouraged him to study law there.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 25</ref> He went to Melbourne to further his studies on Law in 1985.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 31</ref> He applied for scholarship from ITM but was denied. Therefore, he decided to take a study loan instead.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 28</ref> He subsequently obtained [[Bachelor of Laws|Bachelor of Laws (LL.B)]] from the [[University of Melbourne]], [[Australia]] in 1986.<ref name=\"history\"/> After his graduation in Australia, Baru decided to come back to Malaysia to serve the needy instead of applying for permanent residency in Australia.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 145</ref>\n\n===Law career===\nUpon graduation, he became a trainee in a law firm named Rashid & Lee in [[Kuala Lumpur]] for six months before the law firm stopped paying allowances due to financial difficulties. He then continued his training at Eddy Chung & Co and was employed there until he returned to Kuching in 1988.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 146</ref> Baru was subsequently admitted to the [[Malaysian Bar|Malayan Bar]] as a lawyer and [[solicitor]].<ref name=\"history\"/> By 1990, Baru became a partner in the firm of Messrs Anthony Ting, Baru Bian & Co. in Kuching, Sarawak.<ref name=\"Baru Bian CV\"/> Baru taught himself about native customary rights law through Sahabat Alam Malaysia (SAM), an NGO led by [[Harrison Ngau Laing]], an environmentalist. Baru would later became a legal advisor for SAM.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 147</ref> In the same year, he represented SAM to [[Yokohama]], [[Japan]] to protest against the [[International Tropical Timber Organization]] (ITTO) for not including the issues of native customary rights in their report. It was also at this time that Baru Bian met the Swiss activist, [[Bruno Manser]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 147</ref> Bruno would later helped Baru to raise RM 30,000 from overseas supporters to fund Baru's [[1991 Sarawak state election|1991 election]] endeavour.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 148</ref> However, Malaysian embassy officials would later took a photo of Baru Bian and Bruno Manser in Yokohama and used the photo to depict Baru as a traitor to Malaysian interests in 1991 election.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 151</ref>\n\nBaru filed his first NCR case in 1991 on behalf of his extended family whose ancestral lands in Berunut was encroached by logging companies. However, the case was pending in court after two years. Therefore, Baru and his family members took part in timber blockades which successfully led Samling (a logging company) to compensate them RM 100,000. As part of the agreement, Baru withdrew the court case.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 105-116</ref><ref name=\"Fighter\"/> He set up Messrs Baru Bian Advocates and Solicitors in [[Kuching]] in 1992.<ref name=\"history\"/> Baru would later found a legal partner named See Chee How. See is a human rights activist and a lawyer from Kuching. Together, they were involved in numerous native land rights cases.<ref name=\"Money Logging\"/> Baru also took up cases related to wrongful arrests or jailed without [[Remand (detention)|remand]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 119-120</ref> In 2001, Baru Bian won the Rumah Nor Nyawai case in Sarawak High Court. This was the first time in the history of Malaysian courts that NCR rights was upheld.<ref name=\"Money Logging\">{{cite book |last1=Lukas |first1=Straumann |title=Money Logging On the Trail of the Asian Timber Mafia |date=2014 |publisher=[[Bergli Books]] |location=Basel, Switzerland |isbn=978-3-905252-72-9 |pages=205 |edition=First |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-F8aCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT205&lpg=PT205&dq=Rumah+Nor+case+Baru+Bian&source=bl&ots=4zYK2xKiqv&sig=Qr2nH7ho0bjG07J476ClvMBtxow&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwi7puTQw_DeAhUKKo8KHeyJC9EQ6AEwC3oECAAQAQ#v=onepage&q=Rumah%20Nor%20case%20Baru%20Bian&f=false |accessdate=2 November 2018 |language=English |chapter= Chapter 6 -  Bruno Manser's legacy}}</ref> In 2007, the [[Federal Court of Malaysia]] upheld the decision on Rumah Nor Nyawai case that ''pemakai menua'' and ''pulau galau'', in addition to ''temuda'' (cultivated land before 1 January 1958) are included in the definition of NCR land.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 128</ref> In March 2011, Baru successfully led to the acquittal of Numpang Suntai who was accused of burning ten items of machinery in a logging camp at Sebangan, [[Simunjan District]] for encroaching the latter's ancestral land.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 120</ref> By 2013, Baru Bian's law firm had processed more than 200 native land rights cases in court.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 131</ref>\n\nBaru Bian's belief in the freedom of religion guaranteed by the [[Constitution of Malaysia]] had prompted him to take up cases for those who wished to leave the religion of Islam.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Baru |first1=Bian |title=Baru Bian: Court of Appeal Decision a Letdown for converts out of Islam |url=https://www.borneotoday.net/baru-bian-court-of-appeal-decision-a-letdown-for-converts-out-of-islam/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |agency=Press statement |publisher=Borneo Today |date=12 November 2016 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117020750/https://www.borneotoday.net/baru-bian-court-of-appeal-decision-a-letdown-for-converts-out-of-islam/ |archivedate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Wanita Melayu Diwakili Peguam Baru Bian Gagal Dalam Rayuan Kes Murtad (A Malay lady who was represented by lawyer Baru Bian lost the appeal in an apostasy case) |url=https://www.menara.my/wanita-melayu-diwakili-peguam-baru-bian-gagal-dalam-rayuan-kes-murtad/ |publisher=menara.my |accessdate=23 December 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223124445/https://www.menara.my/wanita-melayu-diwakili-peguam-baru-bian-gagal-dalam-rayuan-kes-murtad/ |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Law is silent on Muslim converts wishing to leave Islam \u2013 Baru |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=11 February 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180330175031/http://www.theborneopost.com/2017/02/11/law-is-silent-on-muslim-converts-wishing-to-leave-islam-baru/ |archivedate=30 March 2018}}</ref> His representations in the [[apostasy]] cases has drawn criticisms from [[Malaysian Islamic Party]] (PAS), accusing him of contempt against the Islamic religion.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru Bian blasts death threats, insults over apostasy case |url=https://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2018/02/28/baru-bian-blasts-death-threats-insults-over-apostasy-case/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Free Malaysia Today |date=28 February 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title='Baru Bian hina umat Islam Sarawak' (Baru Bian insulted Islam in Sarawak) |url=https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/413661 |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Malaysiakini |date=27 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223132425/https://www.malaysiakini.com/news/413661 |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Kamarul |first1=Zaman Yusoff |title=Baru Bian juara Kristianisasi Sarawak (Baru Bian is the champion of christianisation in Sarawak) |url=http://www.harakahdaily.net/index.php/berita/15-tanah-air/5501-baru-bian-juara-kristianisasi-sarawak |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=Harakah Daily |date=28 February 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180403152628/http://www.harakahdaily.net/index.php/berita/15-tanah-air/5501-baru-bian-juara-kristianisasi-sarawak |archivedate=3 April 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nIn 1987, Baru joined [[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak]] (PBDS) because the party was advocating NCR rights in Sarawak.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 1989, Baru was elected as PBDS Youth Executive Council member.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 171</ref> Baru was also a supreme council member of PBDS.<ref name=\"history\"/> He first contested against Sarawak [[Barisan Nasional]] (BN) governing coalition at [[Lawas (state constituency)|Lawas]] in 1991 but lost. After that, PBDS started negotiating to rejoin Sarawak BN in 1992 and was subsequently admitted into BN in 1994.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Oorjitham|first1=Santha|title=Dayak welfare was his priority|url=http://www2.nst.com.my/nation/general/dayak-welfare-was-his-priority-1.355519|accessdate=17 May 2015|publisher=New Straits Times|date=14 September 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130920085822/http://www.nst.com.my/nation/general/dayak-welfare-was-his-priority-1.355519|archivedate=20 September 2013 }}</ref> One of the condition for PBDS to rejoin BN was to stop raising the NCR issues within the state government. However, Baru Bian decided to continue his pursue towards NCR rights cases in court.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 2004, Baru decided to quit PBDS and went to contest against BN in [[2004 Ba'kelalan by-election|Ba'kelalan by-election]] as an independent but lost again. Baru believed in continuing to uphold the NCR lands among the natives and the need to change the Sarawak state government in order to solve the NCR problems permanently.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> Baru later joined [[Malaysian Dayak Congress]] (MDS). However, MDS did not get registered before [[2006 Sarawak state election]].<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 184</ref> Therefore, Baru contested again for [[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]] under [[Sarawak National Party]] (SNAP) ticket and lost for the third time. He filed an election petition to [[Miri, Malaysia|Miri]] High Court on BN's vote buying activities in Ba'kelalan. However, the petition was struck out on technicality grounds.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 192-193</ref> He then decided to retire from politics because he already lost three times in elections.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/>\n\nHowever, when BN lost its two-thirds majority in the parliament and five states to the opposition during the [[2008 Malaysian general election]], Baru decided to join politics again to strengthen the two-party system. He joined [[Parti Keadilan Rakyat]] (PKR) in the same year.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> In 2009, Baru was appointed as the chairman of PKR Sarawak.<ref name=\"Fighter\"/> He then proceed to win the Ba'kelalan state constituency during [[2011 Sarawak state election]], having defeated the candidate for the BN coalition, Willie Liau, who is also his nephew, by a narrow 473-vote majority.<ref>{{cite news |title=I\u2019m still a winnable candidate in Ba\u2019 Kelalan \u2014 Balang |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/07/22/im-still-a-winnable-candidate-in-ba-kelalan-balang/ |accessdate=1 December 2018 |date=22 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714172227/http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/07/22/im-still-a-winnable-candidate-in-ba-kelalan-balang/ |archivedate=14 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=William |first1=Mangor |title=Baru Bian: Sarawakians want to see changes |url=http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2015/07/23/baru-bian-sarawakians-want-to-see-changes/ |accessdate=1 December 2018 |publisher=Free Malaysia Today |date=23 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304065656/http://www.freemalaysiatoday.com/category/nation/2015/07/23/baru-bian-sarawakians-want-to-see-changes/ |archivedate=4 March 2016}}</ref> In 2015, Sarawak chief minister [[Adenan Satem]] invited Baru Bian to join BN, however, Baru declined the offer.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Philip |first1=Kiew |title=\u2018Join BN, Baru Bian\u2019 |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/05/31/join-bn-baru-bian/ |accessdate=26 January 2019 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=31 May 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618235255/http://www.theborneopost.com/2015/05/31/join-bn-baru-bian/ |archivedate=18 June 2018}}</ref> Baru retained the seat in the [[2016 Sarawak state election]] with an increased majority of 538 votes, also against Willie.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sarawak Polls: Baru Bian retains Ba'kelalan seat |url=https://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/05/144278/sarawak-polls-baru-bian-retains-bakelalan-seat |accessdate=26 November 2018 |agency=New Straits Times |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160508124142/https://www.nst.com.my/news/2016/05/144278/sarawak-polls-baru-bian-retains-bakelalan-seat |archivedate=8 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn [[2013 Malaysian general election]], Baru Bian decided to contest in [[Limbang (federal constituency)|Limbang]] parliamentary seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru confirms standing in Limbang |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/03/09/baru-confirms-standing-in-limbang/ |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=9 March 2013 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181223223450/http://www.theborneopost.com/2013/03/09/baru-confirms-standing-in-limbang/ |archivedate=23 December 2018}}</ref> However, he was defeated by a huge margin against BN.<ref>{{cite news |title=Baru admits stunned by a huge margin |url=https://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-borneo-post/20130507/281930245490336 |accessdate=23 December 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=7 March 2013}}</ref>\nDuring the [[2018 Malaysian general election]], NCR issues at [[Selangau (federal constituency)|Selangau]] prompt Baru to contest for the seat.<ref>{{cite news |title=NCR issues prompted me to stand in Selangau \u2013 Baru |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/04/29/ncr-issues-prompted-me-to-stand-in-selangau-baru/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=29 April 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180430002606/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/04/29/ncr-issues-prompted-me-to-stand-in-selangau-baru/ |archivedate=30 April 2018}}</ref> He subsequently won the parliamentary seat against BN's Rita Sarimah with a majority of 486 votes.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Jane |first1=Moh |title=Baru Bian secures maiden parliament win in Selangau |url=http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/05/10/baru-bian-secures-maiden-parliament-win-in-selangau/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Borneo Post |date=10 May 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180510000120/http://www.theborneopost.com/2018/05/10/baru-bian-secures-maiden-parliament-win-in-selangau/ |archivedate=10 May 2018}}</ref> On 2 July 2018, Baru was sworn-in as the Minister of Works of Malaysia at [[Istana Negara, Jalan Tuanku Abdul Halim|National Palace]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Andrew |first1=Sia |title=Baru Bian, the first Lun Bawang minister, fought hard for Sarawak natives' land rights |url=https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/baru-bian-first-lun-bawang-minister/ |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Star (Malaysia) |date=2 July 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180703133337/https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2018/07/02/baru-bian-first-lun-bawang-minister/ |archivedate=3 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=New members of Malaysia's Cabinet sworn in |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/new-memebrs-of-malaysias-cabinet-sworn-in |accessdate=26 November 2018 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 July 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180911082355/https://www.straitstimes.com/asia/se-asia/new-memebrs-of-malaysias-cabinet-sworn-in |archivedate=11 September 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2020, he and 10 others Member of Parliament lead by [[Mohamed Azmin Ali]] decided to leave [[People's Justice Party, Malaysia|PKR]] and decided to support [[BERSATU]] Prime Minister candidate [[Mahathir Mohamad]] to remain as the Prime Minister. However [[Mahathir Mohamad]] refuse returning as the Prime Minister of Malaysia so [[BERSATU]] nominated [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] as the nominee for the Prime Minister position. After [[PH]] change their support from [[Anwar Ibrahim]] to [[Mahathir Mohamad]] as the Prime Minister, he (Baru Bian) and Jonathan Yasin who are the 11 MP's who's leaving [[People's Justice Party, Malaysia|PKR]] came back supporting [[Mahathir Mohamad]] as the Prime Minister rather than [[Muhyiddin Yassin]]. [[Muhyiddin Yassin]] make a disgusting move by giving an executive position to Jonathan Yasin in his new back-door government. It is said that he (Baru Bian) and 10 others ex-PKR MP's are officially a member of [[BERSATU]].\n\n==Hobbies and interests==\nBaru learned ''Ngajat'' dance during his primary school years at Long Lellang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 11</ref> Baru is able to sing songs in [[alto]] since he was in Form 4.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 3</ref> Baru started to play football while he was in Form 6.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 24</ref>\n\n[[File:BaruBian4.jpg|thumb|Encouraging Youth]]\n\n==Religion==\nBaru was baptised at [[Limbang River]] in 1973 by a New Zealand missionary named Murray Munroe.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> A few months before baptism, a testimony given by a former gangster from Singapore during an Inter-School Christian Fellowship (ISCF) meeting had strengthen Baru's belief in Christianity.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> Baru started to play guitar for Christian songs while he was a member of ISCF at SMK Limbang.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Page 18</ref> He later become the president of ICSF during Form 4 and Form 5. He participated in Young Christian Students Movement (YCSM) year-end mission trips during his secondary school years.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 20-22</ref> During his years at ITM, he attended Full Gospel Assembly Church service at Old Klang Road.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 29</ref> He also attended a Christian Fellowship in ITM.<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 28</ref> When Baru studied at Melbourne, Australia, he attended Overseas Christian Fellowship (OCF).<ref name=\"Awakening\"/><ref group=note>Baru, 2014. Pages 31</ref>\n\n==Election results==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+ '''[[Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]'''\n!|Year\n!|Constituency\n!colspan=2|\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!colspan=2|Opponent(s)\n!|Votes\n!|Pct\n!Ballots cast\n!Majority\n!Turnout\n|-\n|[[1991 Sarawak state election|1991]]\n|'''[[Lawas (state constituency)|Lawas]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak|PBDS]])\n|align=\"right\" |2,433\n|28.59%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Tengah Ali Hassin''' ([[Parti Pesaka Bumiputera Bersatu|'''PBB''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''6,076'''\n|'''71.41%'''\n|8,619\n|3,643\n|74.10%\n|-\n|[[2004 Ba'kelalan by-election|2004]]\n|rowspan=4|'''[[Ba'kelalan (state constituency)|Ba'kelalan]]'''\n|{{Party shading/Independent}} |\n|{{nowrap|Baru Bian}} ([[Independent politician|IND]])\n|align=\"right\" |1,391\n|32.85%\n|{{Party shading/Barisan Nasional}} |\n|'''Nelson Balang Rining''' ([[Progressive Democratic Party (Malaysia)|'''SPDP''']])\n|align=\"right\" |'''2,843'''\n|'''67.15%'''\n|4,313\n|1,452\n|56.04%\n|-\n|[[2006 Sarawak state e