wak|PRS]])\n|align=\"right\" |10,742\n|48.89%\n|22,352\n|486\n|74.44%\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n{{Malaysian Ministers}}\n{{Sarawak-FedRep}}\n{{Seventh Mahathir cabinet}}\n{{Pakatan Harapan}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bian, Baru}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Malaysian lawyers]]\n[[Category:University of Melbourne alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Sarawak]]\n[[Category:Malaysian Christians]]\n[[Category:Parti Bansa Dayak Sarawak politicians]]\n[[Category:Sarawak politicians]]\n[[Category:People's Justice Party (Malaysia) politicians]]\n[[Category:Members of the Sarawak State Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Members of the Dewan Rakyat]]\n", "name_user": "Desmondkho46", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baru_Bian"}
{"title_page": "Bhukant Misra", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n[[Major]] '''Bhukant Mishra''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] (15 June 1941 \u2013 7 June 1984) was an officer in the 15 Kumaon Regiment who was posthumously awarded the [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]], India's highest peacetime military decoration in 26 January 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.honourpoint.in \u203a profile Web results Major Bhukant Mishra AC {{!}} Honourpoint|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in \u203a bhu... BHUKANT MISRA {{!}} Gallantry Awards|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Major]]\n| name          = Bhukant Mishra\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]]\n| image         = \n| image_size    = 250 px\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date |df=yes|1941|06|15}}\n| death_date    = {{death date and age |df=yes|1984|06|07|1941|06|15}}\n| birth_place   = Nowbasta Talipara, [[Agra]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[British India]]\n| death_place   = [[Amritsar]], [[Punjab]], [[India]]\n| allegiance    = {{Flag|British India}}<br>{{Flag|India}}\n| branch        = {{Army|India}}\n| serviceyears  = 1970-1984\n| rank          = [[File:Major of the Indian Army.svg |25 px]] [[Major]]\n| servicenumber = IC-22479\n| unit          = [[Kumaon Regiment|15 Kumaon]]\n| battles       = [[Operation Blue Star]]\n| awards        = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashok Chakra]]\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nMajor Bhukant Mishra was born on  15 June 1941 in the village  Nowbasta Talipara, of Agra in Uttar Pradesh. Son of Shri B L Mishra, Maj Bhukant was commissioned into 15 battalions of the Kumaon Regiment on 4 April 1970.\n\n== Operation Blue Star ==\nThe terrorism was at its peak in Punjab during 1984, and the terrorists had captured the sacred Golden Temple in Amritsar. A decision was taken by the Indian Government to launch a military operation to evacuate the temple and this operation was code-named  as Op Blue Star.\n\nOn  6 June 1984, a Company commanded by  Major Bhukant Mishra was tasked to clear a temple complex. The Complex was very heavily fortified and was converted into impregnable bastion. Earlier attempts to clear the building during the night had suffered very heavy casualties. At 0440 hours one company led by Major Bhukant Mishra advanced behind an Armoured Personnel Carrier, which was soon hit by anti-tank gun fire. At the same time the company came under very heavy fire and suffered eight casualties, including the JCO of the leading platoon.\n\nRealizing the loss of command and control in the leading platoon, Major Bhukant Mishra rushed forward, irrespective of the heavy fire all around and soon established command and control. Two companies were launched at 0530 hours on the next day. Both the companies advanced at the given time but soon came under very heavy fire. Major Bhukant Mishra's company once again suffered very heavy casualties and the advance of this company stalled. Major Bhukant Mishra at this stage stood in front of the company and asked them to follow him and charged at the base of the Complex. This daring act by Major Bhukant Mishra inspired the company and they rushed behind him and gained a foothold.\n\nA light machine gun firing through a pot hole in the base was interfering in the further advance. Major Bhukant Mishra, without bothering for his safety, now crawled towards the base and destroyed the light machine gun and the crew by lobbing a grenade through the pot hole. Immediately after destroying the light machine gun, Major Bhukant Mishra rushed to the steps leading into the Complex. As he was about to enter the Complex, he was hit by a burst of Medium Machine Gun and was martyred.\n\n== Ashok Chakra awardee ==\nMajor Bhukant Mishra displayed courage, bravery and outstanding leadership skills during the entire operation. For his bravery and supreme sacrifice Major Bhukant Misra was posthumously awarded nation's highest gallantry award during peace time \u201cAshok Chakra\u201d.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Template:Ashoka Chakra award recipients}}\n\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Agra]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)]]\n[[Category:Ashoka Chakra]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2020}}\n[[Major]] '''Bhukant Mishra''', [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]] (15 June 1941 \u2013 7 June 1984) was an officer in the 15 Kumaon Regiment who was posthumously awarded the [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashoka Chakra]], India's highest peacetime military decoration in 26 January 1985.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.honourpoint.in \u203a profile Web results Major Bhukant Mishra AC {{!}} Honourpoint|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gallantryawards.gov.in \u203a bhu... BHUKANT MISRA {{!}} Gallantry Awards|title=|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n{{Infobox military person\n| honorific_prefix = [[Major]]\n| name          = Bhukant Mishra\n| honorific_suffix = [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|AC]]\n| image         =\n| image_size    = 250 px\n| caption       = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date |df=yes|1941|06|15}}\n| death_date    = {{death date and age |df=yes|1984|06|07|1941|06|15}}\n| birth_place   = Nowbasta Talipara, [[Agra]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[British India]]\n| death_place   = [[Amritsar]], [[Punjab]], [[India]]\n| allegiance    = {{Flag|India}}\n| branch        = {{Army|India}}\n| serviceyears  = 1970-1984\n| rank          = [[File:Major of the Indian Army.svg |25 px]] [[Major]]\n| servicenumber = IC-22479\n| unit          =  [[Kumaon Regiment|15 Kumaon]]\n| battles       = [[Operation Blue Star]]\n| awards        = [[File:Ashoka Chakra ribbon.svg|30px]] [[Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)|Ashok Chakra]]\n}}\n\n== Early life ==\nMajor Bhukant Mishra was born on  15 June 1941 in the village  Nowbasta Talipara, of Agra in Uttar Pradesh. Son of Shri B L Mishra, Maj Bhukant was commissioned into 15 battalions of the Kumaon Regiment on 4 April 1970.\n\n== Operation Blue Star ==\nThe terrorism was at its peak in Punjab during 1984, and the terrorists had captured the sacred Golden Temple in Amritsar. A decision was taken by the Indian Government to launch a military operation to evacuate the temple and this operation was code-named  as Op Blue Star.\n\nOn  6 June 1984, a Company commanded by  Major Bhukant Mishra was tasked to clear a temple complex. The Complex was very heavily fortified and was converted into impregnable bastion. Earlier attempts to clear the building during the night had suffered very heavy casualties. At 0440 hours one company led by Major Bhukant Mishra advanced behind an Armoured Personnel Carrier, which was soon hit by anti-tank gun fire. At the same time the company came under very heavy fire and suffered eight casualties, including the JCO of the leading platoon.\n\nRealizing the loss of command and control in the leading platoon, Major Bhukant Mishra rushed forward, irrespective of the heavy fire all around and soon established command and control. Two companies were launched at 0530 hours on the next day. Both the companies advanced at the given time but soon came under very heavy fire. Major Bhukant Mishra's company once again suffered very heavy casualties and the advance of this company stalled. Major Bhukant Mishra at this stage stood in front of the company and asked them to follow him and charged at the base of the Complex. This daring act by Major Bhukant Mishra inspired the company and they rushed behind him and gained a foothold.\n\nA light machine gun firing through a pot hole in the base was interfering in the further advance. Major Bhukant Mishra, without bothering for his safety, now crawled towards the base and destroyed the light machine gun and the crew by lobbing a grenade through the pot hole. Immediately after destroying the light machine gun, Major Bhukant Mishra rushed to the steps leading into the Complex. As he was about to enter the Complex, he was hit by a burst of Medium Machine Gun and was martyred.\n\n== Ashok Chakra awardee ==\nMajor Bhukant Mishra displayed courage, bravery and outstanding leadership skills during the entire operation. For his bravery and supreme sacrifice Major Bhukant Misra was posthumously awarded nation's highest gallantry award during peace time \u201cAshok Chakra\u201d.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Template:Ashoka Chakra award recipients}}\n\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Agra]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Ashoka Chakra (military decoration)]]\n[[Category:Ashoka Chakra]]\n", "name_user": "Koushik Pain", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhukant_Misra"}
{"title_page": "Adrian Owen", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name          = Adrian M. Owen\n| image         = Owen_Lecturing.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| citizenship = \n| honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|OBE}}\n| nationality = British\n| education = [[Gravesend Grammar School]]\n| caption       = Adrian Owen lecturing in 2016\n| birth_name    = Adrian Mark Owen\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1966|05|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Gravesend, Kent]], U.K.\n| website = {{URL|https://owenlab.uwo.ca}}\n| workplaces = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Cambridge]]\n* [[MRC Cognition and Brain Sciences Unit]]\n* [[University of Western Ontario]]}}\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University College London]] (BSc)\n* [[Institute of Psychiatry]] (PhD)}}\n}}\n\n'''Adrian Mark Owen''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 17 May 1966) is a British neuroscientist and best-selling author.<ref name=\"ISBN13: 9781501135200\">{{cite book |last=Owen |first1=Adrian |authorlink=Adrian Owen |url=https://www.simonandschuster.ca/books/Into-the-Gray-Zone/Adrian-Owen/9781501135200 |title=Into The Gray Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death |location=New York |publisher=Scribner |date=20 June 2017 }}</ref> He is best known for his 2006 discovery, published in the journal [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], showing that some patients thought to be in a [[persistent vegetative state]] are in fact fully aware and (shown subsequently) able to communicate with the outside world using [[functional magnetic resonance imaging]] (fMRI). In the 2019 [[2019 New Year Honours|New Year Honours List]], Owen was made an Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (OBE) for services to scientific research.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAdrian Owen was born 17 May 1966 in [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]], England, and educated at [[Gravesend Grammar School]], graduating in the same final year class as actor [[Paul Ritter (actor)|Paul Ritter]]. His first degree was in Psychology from [[University College London]] 1985\u20131988. As a student he shared accommodation with Psychologist and best-selling author [[Richard Wiseman]]. Owen completed his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] at the [[Institute of Psychiatry]], London (now part of [[King's College London]]) between 1988 and 1992.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1992, Owen began his post-doctoral research in the Cognitive Neuroscience Unit at the [[Montreal Neurological Institute|Montreal Neurological Institute, McGill University]], working with Michael Petrides and [[Brenda Milner]]. He was awarded The Pinsent Darwin Scholarship by the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1996 and returned to the UK to work at the newly opened [[Wolfson Brain Imaging Centre]], Cambridge. In 1997 he moved to the [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]]'s [[Cognition and Brain Sciences Unit]] (CBU), Cambridge (formally the [[Applied Psychology Unit]]) to set up the neuroimaging programme there and to pursue his research in cognitive neuroscience. He was awarded MRC tenure in 2000 and made Assistant Director of the MRC CBU in 2005, with overall responsibility for the onsite imaging facilities (3T Siemens Tim Trio MRI and 306-channel Elekta-Neuromag MEG systems).\n\nIn 2010, Owen was awarded a $10M Canada Excellence Research Chair in Cognitive Neuroscience and Imaging at [[The University of Western Ontario]] (UWO)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cerc.gc.ca/chairholders-titulaires/former-ancien-eng.aspx|title=Adrian Owen|date=29 November 2012|website=Canada Excellence Research Chairs|access-date=13 April 2016}}</ref> and moved most of his research team to [[Canada]] in order to take up this position in January 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.westernu.ca/2010/05/one-of-britains-best-picks-western/|title = One of Britain's best picks Western|last = Travis|first = Heather|date = 27 May 2010|website = Western News|language = en-US|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019 Owen was the guest for the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[The Life Scientific]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0009ksc</ref>\n\n==Research==\nOver the last 30 years, Owen has published more than 300 peer-reviewed scientific papers and over 40 chapters and books.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.owenlab.uwo.ca/publications/index.html|title = Publications - Owen Lab|website = Western University|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> His work has appeared in many of the world's most prestigious scientific and medical journals, including [[Science (journal)|Science]], [[Nature (journal)|Nature]], [[The Lancet (journal)|The Lancet]] and [[The New England Journal of Medicine]]. His H-Index ([[Google Scholar]]) is currently 101.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.ca/citations?user=wPFn1OsAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Google Scholar - Adrian Owen|date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis early publications on patients with frontal or temporal-lobe excisions<ref name=\"autogenerated632\">{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M |last2=Coleman |first2=Martin R |title=Functional MRI in disorders of consciousness: advantages and limitations |journal=Current Opinion in Neurology |volume=20 |issue=6 |pages=632\u20137 |year=2007 |pmid=17992081 |doi=10.1097/WCO.0b013e3282f15669}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A |last2=Downes |first2=JJ |last3=Sahakian |first3=BJ |last4=Polkey |first4=CE |last5=Robbins |first5=TW |title=Planning and spatial working memory following frontal lobe lesions in man |journal=Neuropsychologia |volume=28 |issue=10 |pages=1021\u201334 |year=1990 |pmid=2267054 |doi=10.1016/0028-3932(90)90137-D}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A |last2=Roberts |first2=AC |last3=Polkey |first3=CE |last4=Sahakian |first4=BJ |last5=Robbins |first5=TW |title=Extra-dimensional versus intra-dimensional set shifting performance following frontal lobe excisions, temporal lobe excisions or amygdalo-hippocampectomy in man |journal=Neuropsychologia |volume=29 |issue=10 |pages=993\u20131006 |year=1991 |pmid=1762678 |doi=10.1016/0028-3932(91)90063-E}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A. M. |last2=James |first2=M. |last3=Leigh |first3=P. N. |last4=Summers |first4=B. A. |last5=Marsden |first5=C. D. |last6=Quinn |first6=N. P. |last7=Lange |first7=K. W. |last8=Robbins |first8=T. W. |title=Fronto-Striatal Cognitive Deficits at Different Stages of Parkinson's Disease |journal=Brain |volume=115 |issue=6 |pages=1727\u201351 |year=1992 |pmid=1486458 |doi=10.1093/brain/115.6.1727|url=https://epub.uni-regensburg.de/25426/1/langekw8.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A |last2=Sahakian |first2=BJ |last3=Semple |first3=J |last4=Polkey |first4=CE |last5=Robbins |first5=TW |title=Visuo-spatial short-term recognition memory and learning after temporal lobe excisions, frontal lobe excisions or amygdalo-hippocampectomy in man |journal=Neuropsychologia |volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201324 |year=1995 |pmid=7731533 |doi=10.1016/0028-3932(94)00098-A}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Morris |first2=Robin G. |last3=Sahakian |first3=Barbara J. |last4=Polkey |first4=Charles E. |last5=Robbins |first5=Trevor W. |title=Double dissociations of memory and executive functions in working memory tasks following frontal lobe excisions, temporal lobe excisions or amygdalo-hippocampectomy in man |journal=Brain |volume=119 |issue=5 |pages=1597\u2013615 |year=1996 |pmid=8931583 |doi=10.1093/brain/119.5.1597|doi-access=free }}</ref> pioneered the use of touch screen based computerised cognitive tests in neuropsychology. Over the last 20 years, these tests have gone on to be used in more than 600 published studies of [[Parkinson's disease]], [[Alzheimer's disease]], [[Huntington's disease]], [[Major depressive disorder|Depression]], [[Schizophrenia]], [[Autism]], [[Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder]] and [[ADHD]], among others.\n\nHis post-doctoral research on [[working memory]] with Michael Petrides, ([[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|PNAS]], [[Cerebral Cortex (journal)|Cerebral Cortex]], [[Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience]], [[Brain (journal)|Brain]] and others) was instrumental in refuting the then prevailing view of lateral [[Frontal lobe|frontal-lobe]] organisation advanced by [[Patricia Goldman-Rakic]] and others, and is still widely cited in that context. His 1996 paper on the organisation of working memory processes within the human frontal lobe continues to be one of the most highly cited articles ever to appear in the scientific journal [[Cerebral Cortex (journal)|Cerebral Cortex]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Evans |first2=Alan C. |last3=Petrides |first3=Michael |title=Evidence for a Two-Stage Model of Spatial Working Memory Processing within the Lateral Frontal Cortex: A Positron Emission Tomography Study |journal=Cerebral Cortex |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=31\u20138 |year=1996 |pmid=8670636 |doi=10.1093/cercor/6.1.31|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nHis 2006 paper in the journal [[Science (journal)|Science]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Coleman |first2=Martin R. |title=Detecting Awareness in the Vegetative State |journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences |volume=1129 |issue=1 |pages=130\u20138 |year=2008 |pmid=18591475 |doi=10.1196/annals.1417.018|bibcode=2008NYASA1129..130O |url=https://orbi.uliege.be/bitstream/2268/130307/1/VS_science2006.pdf }}</ref> demonstrated for the first time that [[functional neuroimaging]] could be used to detect awareness in patients who are incapable of generating any recognised behavioural response and appear to be in a [[vegetative state]]. This landmark discovery has had implications for clinical care, diagnosis, medical ethics and medical/legal decision-making (relating to the prolongation, or otherwise, of life after severe brain injury).<ref name=\"autogenerated632\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fins |first1=JJ |last2=Schiff |first2=ND |title=Shades of Gray: New Insights into the Vegetative State. |journal=[[Hastings Center Report]] |volume=36 |issue=6 |pages=8|year=2006 |doi=10.1353/hcr.2006.0094|pmid=17278863 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Coleman |first2=Martin R. |title=Functional neuroimaging of the vegetative state |journal=Nature Reviews Neuroscience |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=235\u201343 |year=2008 |pmid=18285801 |doi=10.1038/nrn2330}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=AM |last2=Coleman |first2=MR |title=Using neuroimaging to detect awareness in disorders of consciousness |journal=Functional Neurology |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=189\u201394 |year=2008 |pmid=19331781 |url=http://www.functionalneurology.it/index.php?PAGE=article&ID=3329}}</ref> In a follow up paper in 2010 in [[The New England Journal of Medicine]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Monti |first1=Martin M. |last2=Vanhaudenhuyse |first2=Audrey |last3=Coleman |first3=Martin R. |last4=Boly |first4=Melanie |last5=Pickard |first5=John D. |last6=Tshibanda |first6=Luaba |last7=Owen |first7=Adrian M. |last8=Laureys |first8=Steven |title=Willful Modulation of Brain Activity in Disorders of Consciousness |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=362 |issue=7 |pages=579\u201389 |year=2010 |pmid=20130250 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa0905370|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0178bcd686054a6bf4790b2fd610daee5cc40a16 }}</ref> Owen and his team used a similar method to allow a man believed to be in a vegetative state for more than 5 years to answer 'yes' and 'no' questions with responses that were generated solely by changing his brain activity using [[fMRI]].<ref>Boseleys, S [https://www.theguardian.com/science/2010/feb/03/vegetative-state-patient-communication \"Think tennis for yes, home for no: how doctors helped man in vegetative state\"] The Guardian, 3 February 2010.</ref>\n\nThis research attracted international attention from the world's media; it was reported in many hundreds of newspapers around the world (including twice on the front page of ''[[The New York Times]]'' and other quality journals) and has been widely discussed on television (e.g. BBC News,<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8497148.stm|title = Scan unlocks vegetative patients|date = 3 February 2010|newspaper = BBC|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[Channel 4 News]], [[ITN News]], Sky News,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/757251/vegetative-man-talks-using-his-thoughts |title='Vegetative' Man 'Talks' Using His Thoughts |last=Borland |first=Huw |date=4 February 2010 |website=Sky News |language=en-GB |access-date=13 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509012209/http://news.sky.com/story/757251/vegetative-man-talks-using-his-thoughts |archivedate=9 May 2016 }}</ref> CNN<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cnn.com/2010/HEALTH/02/04/vegetative.state/index.html?iref=allsearch|title = 'Vegetative state' man responds to questions|last = Wilkinson|first = Peter|date = 9 February 2010|website = CNN|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>), radio (e.g. BBC World Service<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/news/2010/02/100204_dr_owen.shtml|title = Listen to Dr Adrian Owen|date = 4 February 2010|publisher = BBC World Service|language = en-GB|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>) 'Outlook' documentary, NPR Radio (USA), BBC Radio 1, 2, 3 and 4), in print (e.g. full featured articles in The New Yorker<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/10/15/silent-minds|title = Silent Minds|last = Groopman|first = Jerome|date = 15 October 2007|newspaper = The New Yorker|issn = 0028-792X|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[The Times]], [[The Sunday Times]], [[The Observer Magazine]] etc.) and online (including Nature, Science and [[The Guardian]] podcasts). To date, the discovery has featured prominently in 6 television documentaries including [[60 Minutes]] (USA),<ref>{{Citation|last = cambridgebrainsciences.com|title = Vegetative State|date = 14 April 2014|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=89Y6V340Xpk|accessdate = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama BBC Special Report]] (UK),<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xv4ldq_the-mind-reader-unlocking-my-voice-couchtripper_shortfilms?start=10|title = The Mind Reader - Unlocking My Voice|website = Dailymotion|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[Inside Out (2002 TV programme)|Inside Out (BBC TV series)]] (UK),<ref>{{Citation|last = cambridgebrainsciences.com|title = InsideOut|date = 23 February 2009|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Myf_CtKWNZA|accessdate = 13 April 2016}}</ref> and [[The National (CBC)|CBC The National]] (Canada).<ref>{{Citation|last = cambridgebrainsciences.com|title = Vegetative state brain scanning breakthrough|date = 15 November 2012|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LaiQ7sEVLD8#t=10|accessdate = 13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Owen launched Cambridge Brain Sciences,<ref name=\"Cambridge Brain Sciences\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridgebrainsciences.com/ |title=Cambridge Brain Sciences }}</ref> a free web-based platform for members of the public and the wider scientific community to assess their cognitive function using scientifically proven tests of memory, attention, reasoning and planning. To date, the tests on the site have been taken more than 8 million times by people worldwide.\n\nIn April 2010, Owen and his team published the largest ever public test of computer-based brain training in the journal [[Nature (journal)|Nature]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Hampshire |first2=Adam |last3=Grahn |first3=Jessica A. |last4=Stenton |first4=Robert |last5=Dajani |first5=Said |last6=Burns |first6=Alistair S. |last7=Howard |first7=Robert J. |last8=Ballard |first8=Clive G. |title=Putting brain training to the test |journal=Nature |volume=465 |issue=7299 |pages=775\u20138 |year=2010 |pmid=20407435 |pmc=2884087 |doi=10.1038/nature09042|bibcode=2010Natur.465..775O }}</ref> The study, conducted in conjunction with the [[BBC]], showed that practice on brain training games does not transfer to other mental skills. More than 11,000 adults followed a six-week training regime, completing computer-based tasks on the BBC's website designed to improve reasoning, memory, planning, visuospatial skills and attention.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/apr/20/brain-training-games-iq|title = Brain-training games don't work|last = Rutherford|first = Adam|date = 20 April 2010|newspaper = The Guardian|language = en-GB|issn = 0261-3077|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> Details of the results were revealed on [[BBC1]] in Can You Train Your Brain?, a [[Bang Goes the Theory]] special and published on the same day in [[Nature (journal)|Nature]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last = Katsnelson|first = Alla|date = 20 April 2010|title = No gain from brain training|journal = Nature News|language = en|volume = 464|issue = 7292|pages = 1111|doi = 10.1038/4641111a|pmid = 20414280|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Owen led a study that was published in a weekly peer-reviewed medical journal, [[The Lancet]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last = Cruse|first = Damian|last2 = Chennu|first2 = Srivas|last3 = Chatelle|first3 = Camille|last4 = Bekinschtein|first4 = Tristan A.|last5 = Fern\u00e1ndez-Espejo|first5 = Davinia|last6 = Pickard|first6 = John D.|last7 = Laureys|first7 = Steven|last8 = Owen|first8 = Adrian M.|date = 17 December 2011|title = Bedside detection of awareness in the vegetative state: a cohort study|journal = Lancet|volume = 378|issue = 9809|pages = 2088\u20132094|doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(11)61224-5|issn = 1474-547X|pmid = 22078855|citeseerx = 10.1.1.368.3928}}</ref> The Researchers found a method for assessing whether or not some patients who appear to be vegetative, are in fact, conscious and are just not able to respond. This new method is using [[electroencephalography]] (EEG), which is not only less expensive than MRI, but is also portable and can be taken right to the patients bedside for testing.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Goldfine |last2=Victor|last3=Conte|last4=Bardin|last5=Schiff|title=Reanalysis of \"Bedside detection of awareness in the vegetative state\"|year=2013|journal=Lancet|volume=381|issue=9863|pages=289\u201391|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(13)60125-7 |pmid=23351802|pmc=3641526}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Reanalysis of \"Bedside detection of awareness in the vegetative state: a cohort study\" \u2014 Authors' reply|journal=Lancet|date=2013|volume=381|issue=9863|pages=291\u2013292|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(13)60126-9|pmid=23351803 | last1 = Cruse | first1 = D | last2 = Chennu | first2 = S | last3 = Chatelle | first3 = C | last4 = Bekinschtein | first4 = TA | last5 = Fern\u00e1ndez-Espejo | first5 = D | last6 = Pickard | first6 = JD | last7 = Laureys | first7 = S | last8 = Owen | first8 = AM}}</ref>\n\n==Book==\nIn June 2017, Owen published 'Into The Gray Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death'<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.ca/books/Into-the-Gray-Zone/Adrian-Owen/9781501135217|title=Into the Gray Zone|date=20 June 2017|isbn=9781501135200|language=en|last1=Owen|first1=Adrian}}</ref> a popular science book that told the story of his 20-year quest to show that some patients thought to be in a vegetative state were in fact entirely aware, but incapable of indicating their awareness to the outside world. The book became a best-seller on both sides of the Atlantic and received rave reviews from [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] (\"A riveting read\"), [[The Guardian]] (\"Beautiful and moving\"), [[The Times]] (\"... the shock almost made me drop my book\"), [[The New York Times]] (\"Owen reprises his cases with enthusiasm and empathy\"), [[Daily Mail|The Daily Mail]] (\"Thought-provoking and deeply moving\"), the [[New Statesman]] (\u201c\"A fascinating book, written with evangelical fervor\u2026gripping and moving\"), [[The New Yorker]] (\"Riveting and strangely uplifting\"), [[The Globe and Mail]] (\"The model of how pop science involving sensational subjects should done\"), the [[Winnipeg Free Press]] (\"prepare to be fascinated, astonished, and, at times, moved to tears\"), [[The Mail on Sunday]] (\"fascinating memoir\u2026The Gray Zone reads like a thriller\"), and many others. The book made [[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]] 'Book of The Year',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/review-into-grey-zone-life-death-adrian-owen-5n08wxgbr|title=Book review: Into the Grey Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death by Adrian Owen|last=Davies|first=Review by Helen|date=27 August 2017|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and [[The Times]] 'Book of The Week', it was listed on [[The New Yorker]] list 'What We're Reading This Summer'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/what-were-reading-this-summer-2017|title=What We're Reading This Summer|last=Yorker|first=The New|date=6 July 2017|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> and received 4.8 out of 5 stars on Amazon.<ref>{{cite web |title=Into the Gray Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death |url=https://www.amazon.com/Into-Gray-Zone-Neuroscientist-Explores-ebook/dp/B01MD0SGCA |website=www.amazon.com}}</ref> The book has been translated into multiple languages, including Italian, French, Russian, German, Taiwanese, Japanese, Czech and Polish.\n\n==Other academic roles==\n* Deputy Editor-In-Chief of the [[European Journal of Neuroscience]] (1997\u20132005) \n* Associate Editor of the [[Journal of Neuroscience]] (2006-2012)\n* Member of the Neurosciences and Mental Health Committee of the [[Wellcome Trust]], the UK's largest non-governmental source of funds for biomedical research (2007-2012)\n* Member of the [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Gairdner Medical Review Panel]]. Canada (2012\u20132017) \n* Advisory Board of the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] (2007\u2013present)\n* Member of the [[Wellcome Trust|Wellcome Trust Peer Review Panel]], UK (2012\u2013present)\n* Member of the Peer Review Committee for the [[Canadian Institutes of Health Research]] (2014\u2013present)\n\nOwen also held/holds affiliations with:\n* [[University of Belgrade]], Serbia, Visiting Professor (2000-2001)\n* [[Institute of Psychiatry]], London, UK, Visiting Professor (2008\u2013present)\n* [[Clare Hall, Cambridge]], UK, Official Fellow (2000-2011)\n* [[Robarts Research Institute]], London, Canada, Research Affiliate (2011\u2013present)\n* [[National Core for Neuroethics]], University of British Columbia, Canada, Faculty Affiliate (2012\u2013present)\n*[http://www.rotman.uwo.ca/rotman-members/ Rotman Institute of Philosophy] at Western University, Canada (2012\u2013present)\n*[https://www.ineco.org.ar International Scientific Committee for the Institute of Cognitive Neurology (INECO)] and the INECO Foundation, Argentina (2013\u2013present)\n\n==Awards==\n* The Pinsent Darwin Scholarship by the University of Cambridge (1996)\n* Shortlisted for the Morgan-Stanley 'Great Briton of 2006' prize (2006)\n* Voted 'Scientist to Watch in 2008' by the [[Financial Times|Financial Times, UK]] (2008)\n* Voted one of the 50 most important scientist in the UK in [[The Times|The Times, London]] (2010)\n* Hellmuth Prize for Achievement in Research Award, [[University of Western Ontario|Western University]], London, Canada (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.westernu.ca/2013/05/hellmuth-celebrates-owen-beamish/|title = Hellmuth celebrates Owen, Beamish|last = Mayne|first = Paul|date = 9 May 2013|website = Western News|language = en-US|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (OBE)]] (2019)\n\n==Personal life==\nOwen lives in [[London, Ontario]] and has one son, Jackson. His brother, Christopher J. Owen, is Professor of Physics and Head of the Space Plasma Group at [[University College London]] (UCL) Department of Space and Climate Physics. His sister, Frances Walsh is Safeguarding Nurse for the NHS, in Warwickshire England. For the past twenty-years, Owen has played guitar and sung in various bands made up of fellow scientists and musicians.<ref name=\"Western News 2016-09-22\">{{cite news |url=https://westerngazette.ca/news/scientists-by-day-pop-stars-by-night/article_a82430aa-7c4e-11e6-b7ac-e79b521feac5.html |title=Scientists by day, pop stars by night |work=Western Gazette |date=22 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.owenlab.uwo.ca Adrian Owen's Lab web page].\n* [http://www.cerc.gc.ca/home-accueil-eng.aspx CERC - Canada Excellence Research Chair]\n* [http://cambridgebrainsciences.com Cambridge Brain Sciences, online web-based testing].\n* [http://www.clarehall.cam.ac.uk/index.php?id=662 Clare Hall, Cambridge].\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8497148.stm BBC News coverage of Adrian Owen's research].\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/5320234.stm BBC News coverage of Adrian Owen's research].\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/labuk/results/braintestbritain/1_results_summary.html Brain Test Britain (Bang Goes The Theory)].\n* [https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn19592-take-the-ultimate-intelligence-test.html Adrian Owen's recent collaboration with The New Scientist].\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01ny377 BBC Panorama Documentary \"The Mind Reader: Unlocking My Voice\"].\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Adrian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Gravesend, Kent]]\n[[Category:Canada Research Chairs]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:University of Western Ontario faculty]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gravesend Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Cognitive neuroscientists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox scientist\n| name          = Adrian M. Owen\n| image         = Owen_Lecturing.jpg\n| image_size  = 200px\n| citizenship = \n| honorific_suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|OBE}}\n| nationality = British\n| education = [[Gravesend Grammar School]]\n| caption       = Adrian Owen lecturing in 2016\n| birth_name    = Adrian Mark Owen\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|df=yes|1966|05|17}}\n| birth_place   = [[Gravesend, Kent]], U.K.\n| website = {{URL|https://owenlab.uwo.ca}}\n| workplaces = {{plainlist|\n* [[University of Cambridge]]\n* [[MRC Cognition and Brain Sciences Unit]]\n* [[University of Western Ontario]]}}\n| alma_mater = {{Plainlist|\n* [[University College London]] (BSc)\n* [[Institute of Psychiatry]] (PhD)}}\n}}\n\n'''Adrian Mark Owen''' {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 17 May 1966) is a British neuroscientist and best-selling author.<ref name=\"ISBN13: 9781501135200\">{{cite book |last=Owen |first1=Adrian |authorlink=Adrian Owen |url=https://www.simonandschuster.ca/books/Into-the-Gray-Zone/Adrian-Owen/9781501135200 |title=Into The Gray Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death |location=New York |publisher=Scribner |date=20 June 2017 }}</ref> He is best known for his 2006 discovery, published in the journal [[Science (journal)|''Science'']], showing that some patients thought to be in a [[persistent vegetative state]] are in fact fully aware and (shown subsequently) able to communicate with the outside world using [[functional magnetic resonance imaging]] (fMRI). In the 2019 [[2019 New Year Honours|New Year Honours List]], Owen was made an Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (OBE) for services to scientific research.\n\n==Early life and education==\nAdrian Owen was born 17 May 1966 in [[Gravesend, Kent|Gravesend]], England, and educated at [[Gravesend Grammar School]], graduating in the same final year class as actor [[Paul Ritter (actor)|Paul Ritter]]. His first degree was in Psychology from [[University College London]] 1985\u20131988. As a student he shared accommodation with Psychologist and best-selling author [[Richard Wiseman]]. Owen completed his [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] at the [[Institute of Psychiatry]], London (now part of [[King's College London]]) between 1988 and 1992.\n\n==Career==\nIn 1992, Owen began his post-doctoral research in the Cognitive Neuroscience Unit at the [[Montreal Neurological Institute|Montreal Neurological Institute, McGill University]], working with Michael Petrides and [[Brenda Milner]]. He was awarded The Pinsent Darwin Scholarship by the [[University of Cambridge]] in 1996 and returned to the UK to work at the newly opened [[Wolfson Brain Imaging Centre]], Cambridge. In 1997 he moved to the [[Medical Research Council (UK)|Medical Research Council]]'s [[Cognition and Brain Sciences Unit]] (CBU), Cambridge (formally the [[Applied Psychology Unit]]) to set up the neuroimaging programme there and to pursue his research in cognitive neuroscience. He was awarded MRC tenure in 2000 and made Assistant Director of the MRC CBU in 2005, with overall responsibility for the onsite imaging facilities (3T Siemens Tim Trio MRI and 306-channel Elekta-Neuromag MEG systems).\n\nIn 2010, Owen was awarded a $10M Canada Excellence Research Chair in Cognitive Neuroscience and Imaging at [[The University of Western Ontario]] (UWO)<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cerc.gc.ca/chairholders-titulaires/former-ancien-eng.aspx|title=Adrian Owen|date=29 November 2012|website=Canada Excellence Research Chairs|access-date=13 April 2016}}</ref> and moved most of his research team to [[Canada]] in order to take up this position in January 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.westernu.ca/2010/05/one-of-britains-best-picks-western/|title = One of Britain's best picks Western|last = Travis|first = Heather|date = 27 May 2010|website = Western News|language = en-US|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2019 Owen was the guest for the [[BBC Radio 4]] programme ''[[The Life Scientific]].<ref>https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/m0009ksc</ref>\n\n==Research==\nOver the last 30 years, Owen has published more than 300 peer-reviewed scientific papers and over 40 chapters and books.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.owenlab.uwo.ca/publications/index.html|title = Publications - Owen Lab|website = Western University|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> His work has appeared in many of the world's most prestigious scientific and medical journals, including [[Science (journal)|Science]], [[Nature (journal)|Nature]], [[The Lancet (journal)|The Lancet]] and [[The New England Journal of Medicine]]. His H-Index ([[Google Scholar]]) is currently 101.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.ca/citations?user=wPFn1OsAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Google Scholar - Adrian Owen|date=14 November 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis early publications on patients with frontal or temporal-lobe excisions<ref name=\"autogenerated632\">{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M |last2=Coleman |first2=Martin R |title=Functional MRI in disorders of consciousness: advantages and limitations |journal=Current Opinion in Neurology |volume=20 |issue=6 |pages=632\u20137 |year=2007 |pmid=17992081 |doi=10.1097/WCO.0b013e3282f15669}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A |last2=Downes |first2=JJ |last3=Sahakian |first3=BJ |last4=Polkey |first4=CE |last5=Robbins |first5=TW |title=Planning and spatial working memory following frontal lobe lesions in man |journal=Neuropsychologia |volume=28 |issue=10 |pages=1021\u201334 |year=1990 |pmid=2267054 |doi=10.1016/0028-3932(90)90137-D}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A |last2=Roberts |first2=AC |last3=Polkey |first3=CE |last4=Sahakian |first4=BJ |last5=Robbins |first5=TW |title=Extra-dimensional versus intra-dimensional set shifting performance following frontal lobe excisions, temporal lobe excisions or amygdalo-hippocampectomy in man |journal=Neuropsychologia |volume=29 |issue=10 |pages=993\u20131006 |year=1991 |pmid=1762678 |doi=10.1016/0028-3932(91)90063-E}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A. M. |last2=James |first2=M. |last3=Leigh |first3=P. N. |last4=Summers |first4=B. A. |last5=Marsden |first5=C. D. |last6=Quinn |first6=N. P. |last7=Lange |first7=K. W. |last8=Robbins |first8=T. W. |title=Fronto-Striatal Cognitive Deficits at Different Stages of Parkinson's Disease |journal=Brain |volume=115 |issue=6 |pages=1727\u201351 |year=1992 |pmid=1486458 |doi=10.1093/brain/115.6.1727|url=https://epub.uni-regensburg.de/25426/1/langekw8.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=A |last2=Sahakian |first2=BJ |last3=Semple |first3=J |last4=Polkey |first4=CE |last5=Robbins |first5=TW |title=Visuo-spatial short-term recognition memory and learning after temporal lobe excisions, frontal lobe excisions or amygdalo-hippocampectomy in man |journal=Neuropsychologia |volume=33 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201324 |year=1995 |pmid=7731533 |doi=10.1016/0028-3932(94)00098-A}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Morris |first2=Robin G. |last3=Sahakian |first3=Barbara J. |last4=Polkey |first4=Charles E. |last5=Robbins |first5=Trevor W. |title=Double dissociations of memory and executive functions in working memory tasks following frontal lobe excisions, temporal lobe excisions or amygdalo-hippocampectomy in man |journal=Brain |volume=119 |issue=5 |pages=1597\u2013615 |year=1996 |pmid=8931583 |doi=10.1093/brain/119.5.1597|doi-access=free }}</ref> pioneered the use of touch screen based computerised cognitive tests in neuropsychology. Over the last 20 years, these tests have gone on to be used in more than 600 published studies of [[Parkinson's disease]], [[Alzheimer's disease]], [[Huntington's disease]], [[Major depressive disorder|Depression]], [[Schizophrenia]], [[Autism]], [[Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder]] and [[ADHD]], among others.\n\nHis post-doctoral research on [[working memory]] with Michael Petrides, ([[Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences|PNAS]], [[Cerebral Cortex (journal)|Cerebral Cortex]], [[Journal of Cognitive Neuroscience]], [[Brain (journal)|Brain]] and others) was instrumental in refuting the then prevailing view of lateral [[Frontal lobe|frontal-lobe]] organisation advanced by [[Patricia Goldman-Rakic]] and others, and is still widely cited in that context. His 1996 paper on the organisation of working memory processes within the human frontal lobe continues to be one of the most highly cited articles ever to appear in the scientific journal [[Cerebral Cortex (journal)|Cerebral Cortex]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Evans |first2=Alan C. |last3=Petrides |first3=Michael |title=Evidence for a Two-Stage Model of Spatial Working Memory Processing within the Lateral Frontal Cortex: A Positron Emission Tomography Study |journal=Cerebral Cortex |volume=6 |issue=1 |pages=31\u20138 |year=1996 |pmid=8670636 |doi=10.1093/cercor/6.1.31|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nHis 2006 paper in the journal [[Science (journal)|Science]]<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Coleman |first2=Martin R. |title=Detecting Awareness in the Vegetative State |journal=Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences |volume=1129 |issue=1 |pages=130\u20138 |year=2008 |pmid=18591475 |doi=10.1196/annals.1417.018|bibcode=2008NYASA1129..130O |url=https://orbi.uliege.be/bitstream/2268/130307/1/VS_science2006.pdf }}</ref> demonstrated for the first time that [[functional neuroimaging]] could be used to detect awareness in patients who are incapable of generating any recognised behavioural response and appear to be in a [[vegetative state]]. This landmark discovery has had implications for clinical care, diagnosis, medical ethics and medical/legal decision-making (relating to the prolongation, or otherwise, of life after severe brain injury).<ref name=\"autogenerated632\"/><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Fins |first1=JJ |last2=Schiff |first2=ND |title=Shades of Gray: New Insights into the Vegetative State. |journal=[[Hastings Center Report]] |volume=36 |issue=6 |pages=8|year=2006 |doi=10.1353/hcr.2006.0094|pmid=17278863 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Coleman |first2=Martin R. |title=Functional neuroimaging of the vegetative state |journal=Nature Reviews Neuroscience |volume=9 |issue=3 |pages=235\u201343 |year=2008 |pmid=18285801 |doi=10.1038/nrn2330}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=AM |last2=Coleman |first2=MR |title=Using neuroimaging to detect awareness in disorders of consciousness |journal=Functional Neurology |volume=23 |issue=4 |pages=189\u201394 |year=2008 |pmid=19331781 |url=http://www.functionalneurology.it/index.php?PAGE=article&ID=3329}}</ref> In a follow up paper in 2010 in [[The New England Journal of Medicine]],<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Monti |first1=Martin M. |last2=Vanhaudenhuyse |first2=Audrey |last3=Coleman |first3=Martin R. |last4=Boly |first4=Melanie |last5=Pickard |first5=John D. |last6=Tshibanda |first6=Luaba |last7=Owen |first7=Adrian M. |last8=Laureys |first8=Steven |title=Willful Modulation of Brain Activity in Disorders of Consciousness |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=362 |issue=7 |pages=579\u201389 |year=2010 |pmid=20130250 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa0905370|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/0178bcd686054a6bf4790b2fd610daee5cc40a16 }}</ref> Owen and his team used a similar method to allow a man believed to be in a vegetative state for more than 5 years to answer 'yes' and 'no' questions with responses that were generated solely by changing his brain activity using [[fMRI]].<ref>Boseleys, S [https://www.theguardian.com/science/2010/feb/03/vegetative-state-patient-communication \"Think tennis for yes, home for no: how doctors helped man in vegetative state\"] The Guardian, 3 February 2010.</ref>\n\nThis research attracted international attention from the world's media; it was reported in many hundreds of newspapers around the world (including twice on the front page of ''[[The New York Times]]'' and other quality journals) and has been widely discussed on television (e.g. BBC News,<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8497148.stm|title = Scan unlocks vegetative patients|date = 3 February 2010|newspaper = BBC|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[Channel 4 News]], [[ITN News]], Sky News,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/story/757251/vegetative-man-talks-using-his-thoughts |title='Vegetative' Man 'Talks' Using His Thoughts |last=Borland |first=Huw |date=4 February 2010 |website=Sky News |language=en-GB |access-date=13 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160509012209/http://news.sky.com/story/757251/vegetative-man-talks-using-his-thoughts |archivedate=9 May 2016 }}</ref> CNN<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.cnn.com/2010/HEALTH/02/04/vegetative.state/index.html?iref=allsearch|title = 'Vegetative state' man responds to questions|last = Wilkinson|first = Peter|date = 9 February 2010|website = CNN|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>), radio (e.g. BBC World Service<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/news/2010/02/100204_dr_owen.shtml|title = Listen to Dr Adrian Owen|date = 4 February 2010|publisher = BBC World Service|language = en-GB|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>) 'Outlook' documentary, NPR Radio (USA), BBC Radio 1, 2, 3 and 4), in print (e.g. full featured articles in The New Yorker<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2007/10/15/silent-minds|title = Silent Minds|last = Groopman|first = Jerome|date = 15 October 2007|newspaper = The New Yorker|issn = 0028-792X|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[The Times]], [[The Sunday Times]], [[The Observer Magazine]] etc.) and online (including Nature, Science and [[The Guardian]] podcasts). To date, the discovery has featured prominently in 6 television documentaries including [[60 Minutes]] (USA),<ref>{{Citation|last = cambridgebrainsciences.com|title = Vegetative State|date = 14 April 2014|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=89Y6V340Xpk|accessdate = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama BBC Special Report]] (UK),<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.dailymotion.com/video/xv4ldq_the-mind-reader-unlocking-my-voice-couchtripper_shortfilms?start=10|title = The Mind Reader - Unlocking My Voice|website = Dailymotion|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> [[Inside Out (2002 TV programme)|Inside Out (BBC TV series)]] (UK),<ref>{{Citation|last = cambridgebrainsciences.com|title = InsideOut|date = 23 February 2009|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Myf_CtKWNZA|accessdate = 13 April 2016}}</ref> and [[The National (CBC)|CBC The National]] (Canada).<ref>{{Citation|last = cambridgebrainsciences.com|title = Vegetative state brain scanning breakthrough|date = 15 November 2012|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=LaiQ7sEVLD8#t=10|accessdate = 13 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, Owen launched Cambridge Brain Sciences,<ref name=\"Cambridge Brain Sciences\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cambridgebrainsciences.com/ |title=Cambridge Brain Sciences }}</ref> a free web-based platform for members of the public and the wider scientific community to assess their cognitive function using scientifically proven tests of memory, attention, reasoning and planning. To date, the tests on the site have been taken more than 8 million times by people worldwide.\n\nIn April 2010, Owen and his team published the largest ever public test of computer-based brain training in the journal [[Nature (journal)|Nature]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Owen |first1=Adrian M. |last2=Hampshire |first2=Adam |last3=Grahn |first3=Jessica A. |last4=Stenton |first4=Robert |last5=Dajani |first5=Said |last6=Burns |first6=Alistair S. |last7=Howard |first7=Robert J. |last8=Ballard |first8=Clive G. |title=Putting brain training to the test |journal=Nature |volume=465 |issue=7299 |pages=775\u20138 |year=2010 |pmid=20407435 |pmc=2884087 |doi=10.1038/nature09042|bibcode=2010Natur.465..775O }}</ref> The study, conducted in conjunction with the [[BBC]], showed that practice on brain training games does not transfer to other mental skills. More than 11,000 adults followed a six-week training regime, completing computer-based tasks on the BBC's website designed to improve reasoning, memory, planning, visuospatial skills and attention.<ref>{{Cite news|url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2010/apr/20/brain-training-games-iq|title = Brain-training games don't work|last = Rutherford|first = Adam|date = 20 April 2010|newspaper = The Guardian|language = en-GB|issn = 0261-3077|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref> Details of the results were revealed on [[BBC1]] in Can You Train Your Brain?, a [[Bang Goes the Theory]] special and published on the same day in [[Nature (journal)|Nature]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last = Katsnelson|first = Alla|date = 20 April 2010|title = No gain from brain training|journal = Nature News|language = en|volume = 464|issue = 7292|pages = 1111|doi = 10.1038/4641111a|pmid = 20414280|doi-access = free}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2011, Owen led a study that was published in a weekly peer-reviewed medical journal, [[The Lancet]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last = Cruse|first = Damian|last2 = Chennu|first2 = Srivas|last3 = Chatelle|first3 = Camille|last4 = Bekinschtein|first4 = Tristan A.|last5 = Fern\u00e1ndez-Espejo|first5 = Davinia|last6 = Pickard|first6 = John D.|last7 = Laureys|first7 = Steven|last8 = Owen|first8 = Adrian M.|date = 17 December 2011|title = Bedside detection of awareness in the vegetative state: a cohort study|journal = Lancet|volume = 378|issue = 9809|pages = 2088\u20132094|doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(11)61224-5|issn = 1474-547X|pmid = 22078855|citeseerx = 10.1.1.368.3928}}</ref> The Researchers found a method for assessing whether or not some patients who appear to be vegetative, are in fact, conscious and are just not able to respond. This new method is using [[electroencephalography]] (EEG), which is not only less expensive than MRI, but is also portable and can be taken right to the patients bedside for testing.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Goldfine |last2=Victor|last3=Conte|last4=Bardin|last5=Schiff|title=Reanalysis of \"Bedside detection of awareness in the vegetative state\"|year=2013|journal=Lancet|volume=381|issue=9863|pages=289\u201391|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(13)60125-7 |pmid=23351802|pmc=3641526}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Reanalysis of \"Bedside detection of awareness in the vegetative state: a cohort study\" \u2014 Authors' reply|journal=Lancet|date=2013|volume=381|issue=9863|pages=291\u2013292|doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(13)60126-9|pmid=23351803 | last1 = Cruse | first1 = D | last2 = Chennu | first2 = S | last3 = Chatelle | first3 = C | last4 = Bekinschtein | first4 = TA | last5 = Fern\u00e1ndez-Espejo | first5 = D | last6 = Pickard | first6 = JD | last7 = Laureys | first7 = S | last8 = Owen | first8 = AM}}</ref>\n\n==Book==\nIn June 2017, Owen published 'Into The Gray Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death'<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.simonandschuster.ca/books/Into-the-Gray-Zone/Adrian-Owen/9781501135217|title=Into the Gray Zone|date=20 June 2017|isbn=9781501135200|language=en|last1=Owen|first1=Adrian}}</ref> a popular science book that told the story of his 20-year quest to show that some patients thought to be in a vegetative state were in fact entirely aware, but incapable of indicating their awareness to the outside world. The book became a best-seller on both sides of the Atlantic and received rave reviews from [[Nature (journal)|Nature]] (\"A riveting read\"), [[The Guardian]] (\"Beautiful and moving\"), [[The Times]] (\"... the shock almost made me drop my book\"), [[The New York Times]] (\"Owen reprises his cases with enthusiasm and empathy\"), [[Daily Mail|The Daily Mail]] (\"Thought-provoking and deeply moving\"), the [[New Statesman]] (\u201c\"A fascinating book, written with evangelical fervor\u2026gripping and moving\"), [[The New Yorker]] (\"Riveting and strangely uplifting\"), [[The Globe and Mail]] (\"The model of how pop science involving sensational subjects should done\"), the [[Winnipeg Free Press]] (\"prepare to be fascinated, astonished, and, at times, moved to tears\"), [[The Mail on Sunday]] (\"fascinating memoir\u2026The Gray Zone reads like a thriller\"), and many others. The book made [[The Sunday Times|Sunday Times]] 'Book of The Year',<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/review-into-grey-zone-life-death-adrian-owen-5n08wxgbr|title=Book review: Into the Grey Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death by Adrian Owen|last=Davies|first=Review by Helen|date=27 August 2017|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> and [[The Times]] 'Book of The Week', it was listed on [[The New Yorker]] list 'What We're Reading This Summer'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/books/page-turner/what-were-reading-this-summer-2017|title=What We're Reading This Summer|last=Yorker|first=The New|date=6 July 2017|access-date=7 September 2019|language=en|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> and received 4.8 out of 5 stars on Amazon.<ref>{{cite web |title=Into the Gray Zone: A Neuroscientist Explores the Border Between Life and Death |url=https://www.amazon.com/Into-Gray-Zone-Neuroscientist-Explores-ebook/dp/B01MD0SGCA |website=www.amazon.com}}</ref> The book has been translated into multiple languages, including Italian, French, Russian, German, Taiwanese, Japanese, Czech and Polish.\n\n==Other academic roles==\n* Deputy Editor-In-Chief of the [[European Journal of Neuroscience]] (1997\u20132005) \n* Associate Editor of the [[Journal of Neuroscience]] (2006-2012)\n* Member of the Neurosciences and Mental Health Committee of the [[Wellcome Trust]], the UK's largest non-governmental source of funds for biomedical research (2007-2012)\n* Member of the [[Gairdner Foundation International Award|Gairdner Medical Review Panel]]. Canada (2012\u20132017) \n* Advisory Board of the [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] (2007\u2013present)\n* Member of the [[Wellcome Trust|Wellcome Trust Peer Review Panel]], UK (2012\u2013present)\n* Member of the Peer Review Committee for the [[Canadian Institutes of Health Research]] (2014\u2013present)\n\nOwen also held/holds affiliations with:\n* [[University of Belgrade]], Serbia, Visiting Professor (2000-2001)\n* [[Institute of Psychiatry]], London, UK, Visiting Professor (2008\u2013present)\n* [[Clare Hall, Cambridge]], UK, Official Fellow (2000-2011)\n* [[Robarts Research Institute]], London, Canada, Research Affiliate (2011\u2013present)\n* [[National Core for Neuroethics]], University of British Columbia, Canada, Faculty Affiliate (2012\u2013present)\n*[http://www.rotman.uwo.ca/rotman-members/ Rotman Institute of Philosophy] at Western University, Canada (2012\u2013present)\n*[https://www.ineco.org.ar International Scientific Committee for the Institute of Cognitive Neurology (INECO)] and the INECO Foundation, Argentina (2013\u2013present)\n\n==Awards==\n* The Pinsent Darwin Scholarship by the University of Cambridge (1996)\n* Shortlisted for the Morgan-Stanley 'Great Briton of 2006' prize (2006)\n* Voted 'Scientist to Watch in 2008' by the [[Financial Times|Financial Times, UK]] (2008)\n* Voted one of the 50 most important scientist in the UK in [[The Times|The Times, London]] (2010)\n* Hellmuth Prize for Achievement in Research Award, [[University of Western Ontario|Western University]], London, Canada (2013)<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://news.westernu.ca/2013/05/hellmuth-celebrates-owen-beamish/|title = Hellmuth celebrates Owen, Beamish|last = Mayne|first = Paul|date = 9 May 2013|website = Western News|language = en-US|access-date = 13 April 2016}}</ref>\n*[[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Most Excellent Order of the British Empire (OBE)]] (2019)\n\n==Personal life==\nOwen lives in [[London, Ontario]] and has one son, Jackson. His brother, Christopher J. Owen, is Professor of Physics and Head of the Space Plasma Group at [[University College London]] (UCL) Department of Space and Climate Physics. His sister, Frances Walsh is Safeguarding Nurse for the NHS, in Warwickshire England. For the past twenty-years, Owen has played guitar and sung in various bands made up of fellow scientists and musicians.<ref name=\"Western News 2016-09-22\">{{cite news |url=https://westerngazette.ca/news/scientists-by-day-pop-stars-by-night/article_a82430aa-7c4e-11e6-b7ac-e79b521feac5.html |title=Scientists by day, pop stars by night |work=Western Gazette |date=22 September 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.owenlab.uwo.ca] Adrian Owen's Lab web page.\n* [http://www.cerc.gc.ca/home-accueil-eng.aspx] CERC - Canada Excellence Research Chair\n* [http://cambridgebrainsciences.com] Cambridge Brain Sciences, online web-based testing.\n* [http://www.clarehall.cam.ac.uk/index.php?id=662] Clare Hall, Cambridge.\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/8497148.stm] BBC News coverage of Adrian Owen's research.\n* [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/health/5320234.stm] BBC News coverage of Adrian Owen's research.\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/labuk/results/braintestbritain/1_results_summary.html] Brain Test Britain (Bang Goes The Theory).\n* [https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn19592-take-the-ultimate-intelligence-test.html] Adrian Owen's recent collaboration with The New Scientist.\n* [https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01ny377] BBC Panorama Documentary \"The Mind Reader: Unlocking My Voice\".\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Adrian}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:British neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Gravesend, Kent]]\n[[Category:Canada Research Chairs]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:University of Western Ontario faculty]]\n[[Category:People educated at Gravesend Grammar School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:Cognitive neuroscientists]]\n", "name_user": "Khoshhat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adrian_Owen"}
{"title_page": "John of Patmos", "text_new": "{{short description|Christian saint and author of the Book of Revelation}}\n{{Redirect2|John the Divine|John the Revelator|other uses of John the Divine|John the Divine (disambiguation)|other uses of John the Revelator|John the Revelator (disambiguation)|other people called Saint John|Saint John (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox saint\n|name=John of Patmos\n|birth_date=6 AD\n|death_date=~100 AD\n|feast_day=\n|venerated_in= [[Catholic Church]]<br/>[[Eastern Orthodox Church]] \n|image=File:Antonio Palomino 003.JPG\n|imagesize=250px\n|caption=''Saint John the Evangelist on Patmos'' by [[Antonio Palomino]], 17th century\n|death_place=[[Ephesus]], [[Roman Empire]] (?)\n|birth_place= [[Pool of Bethesda]], [[Jerusalem]]\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|major_works=[[Book of Revelation]]\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n|prayer=\n|prayer_attrib=\n}}\n{{John}}\n'''John of Patmos''' (also called '''John the Retarded''', '''John the Derp''', '''John the Turdbubble''', and not possibly [[John the Apostle]]; [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u1f38\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u1f41 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2; {{lang-cop|\u2c93\u2cb1\u2c81\u2c9b\u2c9b\u2c8f\u2ca5}}) could be the author named as John in the [[Book of Revelation]], the [[Apocalyptic literature|apocalyptic]] text forming the stupidest book of the [[New Testament]]. The text of Revelation states that John was on [[Patmos]], a [[Greece|Greek]] island where, by most biblical historians, he is considered to be exiled as a result of anti-Christian persecution under the Roman emperor [[Domitian]].<ref>Souvay, Charles. [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11547a.htm \"Patmos.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia.'' Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 12 Jan. 2009</ref><ref>Phillips, J. B. {{cite web |url=http://www.ccel.org/bible/phillips/CPn27Revelation.htm |title= Book 27 - Book of Revelation |author= |date=12 January 1962 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=}} ''People, Places, Customs, Concepts, Journeys - the New Testament with integrated notes and maps 1962.</ref> \n\nSince the Roman era, Christians and historians have considered the Book of Revelation's writer to be an impostor of the Apostle John (John the Evangelist), author of the [[Gospel of John]]. However, a minority of senior clerics and scholars, such as [[Eusebius]] (d. 339/340), recognize at least one further John as a companion of Jesus Christ, [[John the Presbyter]] \"after an interval, placing him among others outside of the number of the apostles\". Some Christian scholars since medieval times separate the disciple(s) from Revelation's writer, John of Patmos/the Divine.<ref name=Harris>Stephen L Harris, ''Understanding the Bible,'' (Palo Alto: Mayfield, 1985), 355</ref><ref name=Ehrman>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Book of Revelation ==\nThe author of the [[Book of Revelation]] identifies himself only as \"John\".<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\">\"Revelation, Book of.\" Cross, F. L., ed. The Oxford dictionary of the Christian church. New York: Oxford University Press. 2005</ref> Traditionally, this was often believed to be the same person as [[John the Apostle|John, son of Zebedee]], one of the apostles of Jesus, to whom the [[Gospel of John]] was also attributed.<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\"/> The early-2nd-century writer, [[Justin Martyr]], was the first to equate the author of Revelation with [[John the Evangelist]].<ref name=\"Justin\">Justin Martyr, ''Dialogue with Trypho'', 81.4</ref> Other early Christian writers, however, such as [[Dionysius of Alexandria]] and [[Eusebius of Caesarea]], noting the  differences in language and theological outlook between this work and the Gospel,<ref>Ben Witherington, ''Revelation'', (Cambridge University Press) page 2.</ref> discounted this possibility, and argued for the exclusion of the Book of Revelation from the canon as a result.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=432 }}</ref> The early Christian writer [[Papias of Hierapolis|Papias]] appeared in his writings to distinguish between [[John the Evangelist]] and [[John the Elder]],<ref>Richard Bauckham, ''Jesus and the Eyewitnesses'' (William B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2006)</ref> and many biblical scholars now contend that the latter was the author of Revelation.<ref>Robert H. Mounce, ''The Book of Revelation'' (Wm B. Eerdmans Publications) page 10.</ref><ref>[[Stephen L Harris|Harris, Stephen L.]], ''Understanding the Bible''. Palo Alto: Mayfield. 1985. p. 355</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=''The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings'' |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Island of Patmos ==\nJohn is considered to be exiled to [[Patmos]] due to mental deficiency, undergoing a time of persecution under the Roman rule of [[Domitian]]. ''Revelation 1:9'' states: \"''I, John, both your brother and companion in tribulation...was on the island that is called Patmos for the word of GOD and for the testimony of Jesus Christ''.\" [[Adela Yarbro Collins]], a biblical scholar at [[Yale Divinity School]], writes:\n<blockquote>Early tradition says that John was banished to Patmos by the Roman authorities. This tradition is credible because banishment was a common punishment used during the Imperial period for a number of offenses. Among such offenses were the practices of magic and astrology. Prophecy was viewed by the Romans as belonging to the same category, whether Pagan, Jewish, or Christian. Prophecy with political implications, like that expressed by John in the Book of Revelation, would have been perceived as a threat to Roman political power and order. Three of the islands in the [[Sporades]] were places where political offenders were banished. (Pliny, ''Natural History'' 4.69&ndash;70; Tacitus, ''Annals'' 4.30)<ref>Adela Collins. (1985). \"Patmos\" [In] Paul J. Achtemeier [Ed.]. (1985) ''Harper's Bible Dictionary''. San Francisco, CA: Harper & Row. p.&nbsp;755.</ref></blockquote>\n\nJohn was allegedly banished by the Roman authorities to the Greek island of [[Patmos]], where, according to tradition, he wrote the [[Book of Revelation]]. According to [[Tertullian]] (in ''The Prescription of Heretics'') John was banished (presumably to Patmos) after being plunged into boiling oil in Rome and suffering nothing from it. It is said that all in the audience of the Colosseum were converted to Christianity upon witnessing this miracle.<ref>citation needed</ref> This event would have occurred in the late 1st&nbsp;century, during the reign of the Emperor [[Domitian]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Authorship of the Johannine works]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Wikiquote-inline}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Apostles}}\n{{Book of Revelation}}\n{{New Testament people|prophets|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John Of Patmos}}\n[[Category:1st-century apocalypticists]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christians]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:2nd-century Christians]]\n[[Category:Angelic visionaries]]\n[[Category:Book of Revelation]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Christian writers about eschatology]]\n[[Category:Jewish Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:John the Apostle]]\n[[Category:Patmos]]\n[[Category:People from Patmos]]\n[[Category:Prophets of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Saints from the Holy Land]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Christian saint and author of the Book of Revelation}}\n{{Redirect2|John the Divine|John the Revelator|other uses of John the Divine|John the Divine (disambiguation)|other uses of John the Revelator|John the Revelator (disambiguation)|other people called Saint John|Saint John (disambiguation)}}\n\n{{Infobox saint\n|name=John of Patmos\n|birth_date=6 AD\n|death_date=~100 AD\n|feast_day=\n|venerated_in= [[Catholic Church]]<br/>[[Eastern Orthodox Church]] \n|image=File:Antonio Palomino 003.JPG\n|imagesize=250px\n|caption=''Saint John the Evangelist on Patmos'' by [[Antonio Palomino]], 17th century\n|death_place=[[Ephesus]], [[Roman Empire]] (?)\n|birth_place= [[Pool of Bethesda]], [[Jerusalem]]\n|beatified_date=\n|beatified_place=\n|beatified_by=\n|canonized_date=\n|major_works=[[Book of Revelation]]\n|canonized_by=\n|attributes=\n|patronage=\n|major_shrine=\n|suppressed_date=\n|issues=\n|prayer=\n|prayer_attrib=\n}}\n{{John}}\n'''John of Patmos''' (also called '''John the Revelator''', '''John the Divine''', '''John the Theologian''', and possibly [[John the Apostle]]; [[Ancient Greek|Greek]]: \u1f38\u03c9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b7\u03c2 \u1f41 \u0398\u03b5\u03bf\u03bb\u03cc\u03b3\u03bf\u03c2; {{lang-cop|\u2c93\u2cb1\u2c81\u2c9b\u2c9b\u2c8f\u2ca5}}) could be the author named as John in the [[Book of Revelation]], the [[Apocalyptic literature|apocalyptic]] text forming the final book of the [[New Testament]]. The text of Revelation states that John was on [[Patmos]], a [[Greece|Greek]] island where, by most biblical historians, he is considered to be exiled as a result of anti-Christian persecution under the Roman emperor [[Domitian]].<ref>Souvay, Charles. [http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/11547a.htm \"Patmos.\"] ''The Catholic Encyclopedia.'' Vol. 11. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1911. 12 Jan. 2009</ref><ref>Phillips, J. B. {{cite web |url=http://www.ccel.org/bible/phillips/CPn27Revelation.htm |title= Book 27 - Book of Revelation |author= |date=12 January 1962 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=}} ''People, Places, Customs, Concepts, Journeys - the New Testament with integrated notes and maps 1962.</ref> \n\nSince the Roman era, Christians and historians have considered the Book of Revelation's writer to be the Apostle John (John the Evangelist), author of the [[Gospel of John]]. However, a minority of senior clerics and scholars, such as [[Eusebius]] (d. 339/340), recognize at least one further John as a companion of Jesus Christ, [[John the Presbyter]] \"after an interval, placing him among others outside of the number of the apostles\". Some Christian scholars since medieval times separate the disciple(s) from Revelation's writer, John of Patmos/the Divine.<ref name=Harris>Stephen L Harris, ''Understanding the Bible,'' (Palo Alto: Mayfield, 1985), 355</ref><ref name=Ehrman>{{Cite book|last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Book of Revelation ==\nThe author of the [[Book of Revelation]] identifies himself only as \"John\".<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\">\"Revelation, Book of.\" Cross, F. L., ed. The Oxford dictionary of the Christian church. New York: Oxford University Press. 2005</ref> Traditionally, this was often believed to be the same person as [[John the Apostle|John, son of Zebedee]], one of the apostles of Jesus, to whom the [[Gospel of John]] was also attributed.<ref name=\"ODCC Revelation, Book of\"/> The early-2nd-century writer, [[Justin Martyr]], was the first to equate the author of Revelation with [[John the Evangelist]].<ref name=\"Justin\">Justin Martyr, ''Dialogue with Trypho'', 81.4</ref> Other early Christian writers, however, such as [[Dionysius of Alexandria]] and [[Eusebius of Caesarea]], noting the  differences in language and theological outlook between this work and the Gospel,<ref>Ben Witherington, ''Revelation'', (Cambridge University Press) page 2.</ref> discounted this possibility, and argued for the exclusion of the Book of Revelation from the canon as a result.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings |year=2000 |publisher=Oxford University Press |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=432 }}</ref> The early Christian writer [[Papias of Hierapolis|Papias]] appeared in his writings to distinguish between [[John the Evangelist]] and [[John the Elder]],<ref>Richard Bauckham, ''Jesus and the Eyewitnesses'' (William B. Eerdmans Publishing, 2006)</ref> and many biblical scholars now contend that the latter was the author of Revelation.<ref>Robert H. Mounce, ''The Book of Revelation'' (Wm B. Eerdmans Publications) page 10.</ref><ref>[[Stephen L Harris|Harris, Stephen L.]], ''Understanding the Bible''. Palo Alto: Mayfield. 1985. p. 355</ref><ref>{{cite book |last=Ehrman |first=Bart D.|authorlink=Bart D. Ehrman |title=''The New Testament: A Historical Introduction to the Early Christian Writings'' |year=2004 |publisher=Oxford |location=New York |isbn=0-19-515462-2 |page=468 }}</ref>\n\n== Island of Patmos ==\nJohn is considered to be exiled to [[Patmos]], undergoing a time of persecution under the Roman rule of [[Domitian]]. ''Revelation 1:9'' states: \"''I, John, both your brother and companion in tribulation...was on the island that is called Patmos for the word of GOD and for the testimony of Jesus Christ''.\" [[Adela Yarbro Collins]], a biblical scholar at [[Yale Divinity School]], writes:\n<blockquote>Early tradition says that John was banished to Patmos by the Roman authorities. This tradition is credible because banishment was a common punishment used during the Imperial period for a number of offenses. Among such offenses were the practices of magic and astrology. Prophecy was viewed by the Romans as belonging to the same category, whether Pagan, Jewish, or Christian. Prophecy with political implications, like that expressed by John in the Book of Revelation, would have been perceived as a threat to Roman political power and order. Three of the islands in the [[Sporades]] were places where political offenders were banished. (Pliny, ''Natural History'' 4.69&ndash;70; Tacitus, ''Annals'' 4.30)<ref>Adela Collins. (1985). \"Patmos\" [In] Paul J. Achtemeier [Ed.]. (1985) ''Harper's Bible Dictionary''. San Francisco, CA: Harper & Row. p.&nbsp;755.</ref></blockquote>\n\nJohn was allegedly banished by the Roman authorities to the Greek island of [[Patmos]], where, according to tradition, he wrote the [[Book of Revelation]]. According to [[Tertullian]] (in ''The Prescription of Heretics'') John was banished (presumably to Patmos) after being plunged into boiling oil in Rome and suffering nothing from it. It is said that all in the audience of the Colosseum were converted to Christianity upon witnessing this miracle.<ref>citation needed</ref> This event would have occurred in the late 1st&nbsp;century, during the reign of the Emperor [[Domitian]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Authorship of the Johannine works]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Wikiquote-inline}}\n\n{{-}}\n{{Apostles}}\n{{Book of Revelation}}\n{{New Testament people|prophets|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:John Of Patmos}}\n[[Category:1st-century apocalypticists]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christians]]\n[[Category:1st-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:1st-century writers]]\n[[Category:2nd-century Christians]]\n[[Category:Angelic visionaries]]\n[[Category:Book of Revelation]]\n[[Category:Christian saints from the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Christian writers about eschatology]]\n[[Category:Jewish Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:John the Apostle]]\n[[Category:Patmos]]\n[[Category:People from Patmos]]\n[[Category:Prophets of the New Testament]]\n[[Category:Saints from the Holy Land]]\n[[Category:Year of birth unknown]]\n", "name_user": "173.246.192.192", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Spelling correction)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_of_Patmos"}
